WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.992 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.992 --> 00:00:04.482 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.482 --> 00:00:07.470 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.470 --> 00:00:11.287 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.287 --> 00:00:12.120 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:14.420 align:middle line:84%
So we're sort of in the
last part of the class now.

00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:18.920 align:middle line:84%
And I've been reflecting
on what to do together.

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:23.200 align:middle line:84%
And I asked everybody for
some input, a little survey

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:26.540 align:middle line:84%
about what topics to do
and how much detail to do.

00:00:26.540 --> 00:00:30.440 align:middle line:84%
And there was no
consensus in the survey

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:34.040 align:middle line:90%
of what people wanted to do.

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:37.640 align:middle line:84%
But I decided I would like
to do, for a couple of weeks,

00:00:37.640 --> 00:00:41.960 align:middle line:84%
talk about some applications of
projection theory in other areas

00:00:41.960 --> 00:00:44.660 align:middle line:84%
and then, the last
couple of weeks,

00:00:44.660 --> 00:00:48.600 align:middle line:84%
try to talk about at least some
of the main ideas in the proof

00:00:48.600 --> 00:00:49.910 align:middle line:90%
of the projection theorem.

00:00:49.910 --> 00:00:52.620 align:middle line:90%


00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:53.120 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:56.720 align:middle line:84%
- So we recently had been doing
Bourgain's projection theorem

00:00:56.720 --> 00:00:59.170 align:middle line:84%
and the Bourgain-Katz-Tao
projection theorem in finite

00:00:59.170 --> 00:01:00.050 align:middle line:90%
fields--

00:01:00.050 --> 00:01:04.930 align:middle line:84%
and so feeling
that we really had

00:01:04.930 --> 00:01:06.970 align:middle line:84%
to work pretty hard
for those things.

00:01:06.970 --> 00:01:09.290 align:middle line:84%
And it was striking that
we had to work pretty hard

00:01:09.290 --> 00:01:13.610 align:middle line:84%
just to get this very
small improvement.

00:01:13.610 --> 00:01:16.830 align:middle line:84%
And so in some of what we'll
do in the rest of the class,

00:01:16.830 --> 00:01:19.613 align:middle line:84%
I will try to show that
that small improvement is

00:01:19.613 --> 00:01:20.280 align:middle line:90%
really valuable.

00:01:20.280 --> 00:01:23.250 align:middle line:90%


00:01:23.250 --> 00:01:24.930 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:24.930 --> 00:01:25.630 align:middle line:90%
So yeah.

00:01:25.630 --> 00:01:29.470 align:middle line:84%
So the plan for the rest of the
class is, for about one week,

00:01:29.470 --> 00:01:31.753 align:middle line:84%
we'll talk about
random walks on groups.

00:01:31.753 --> 00:01:33.170 align:middle line:84%
And then for about
one week, we'll

00:01:33.170 --> 00:01:36.090 align:middle line:90%
talk about homogeneous dynamics.

00:01:36.090 --> 00:01:38.650 align:middle line:84%
And then at the end, we'll
talk about the sharp projection

00:01:38.650 --> 00:01:40.150 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

00:01:40.150 --> 00:01:40.650 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:40.650 --> 00:01:44.290 align:middle line:90%


00:01:44.290 --> 00:01:45.290 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:01:45.290 --> 00:01:47.410 align:middle line:84%
And also, in the
last few classes,

00:01:47.410 --> 00:01:50.710 align:middle line:84%
I felt that we were doing
some very technical things

00:01:50.710 --> 00:01:55.450 align:middle line:84%
and sometimes a little
bit of a struggle.

00:01:55.450 --> 00:01:58.030 align:middle line:84%
So for today, what I
want to do is to give,

00:01:58.030 --> 00:02:00.860 align:middle line:84%
I hope, a very friendly
introduction to random

00:02:00.860 --> 00:02:03.540 align:middle line:84%
walks on groups
and then next week,

00:02:03.540 --> 00:02:06.340 align:middle line:84%
on Tuesday, to explain how
projection theory helps

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:09.373 align:middle line:84%
to figure out some
interesting things.

00:02:09.373 --> 00:02:09.873 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:09.873 --> 00:02:19.250 align:middle line:90%


00:02:19.250 --> 00:02:20.450 align:middle line:90%
So I'll talk about.

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:23.260 align:middle line:90%


00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:26.070 align:middle line:90%
random walks on groups.

00:02:26.070 --> 00:02:32.180 align:middle line:90%


00:02:32.180 --> 00:02:32.680 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:37.140 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that G
is a finite group.

00:02:37.140 --> 00:02:41.340 align:middle line:84%
And then mu is a
probability measure on G.

00:02:41.340 --> 00:02:46.980 align:middle line:84%
So I'll think of it as
a function on G which

00:02:46.980 --> 00:02:50.080 align:middle line:90%
is non-negative and sums to 1.

00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:54.340 align:middle line:90%


00:02:54.340 --> 00:02:54.840 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:54.840 --> 00:02:57.130 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a probability
measure like this,

00:02:57.130 --> 00:03:00.490 align:middle line:84%
you can do a random walk where,
at each step of the random walk,

00:03:00.490 --> 00:03:03.310 align:middle line:84%
you pick an element of
G by this probability,

00:03:03.310 --> 00:03:06.430 align:middle line:84%
and then you move
by that element.

00:03:06.430 --> 00:03:08.040 align:middle line:84%
So here's how the
random walk works.

00:03:08.040 --> 00:03:13.350 align:middle line:90%


00:03:13.350 --> 00:03:18.270 align:middle line:84%
So you start
somewhere, say at g0.

00:03:18.270 --> 00:03:27.590 align:middle line:84%
Then you sample
a step h from mu.

00:03:27.590 --> 00:03:33.427 align:middle line:84%
And the next guy,
g1, is g0 times h.

00:03:33.427 --> 00:03:35.010 align:middle line:84%
So that's one step
of the random walk.

00:03:35.010 --> 00:03:36.385 align:middle line:84%
And then you can
keep doing this.

00:03:36.385 --> 00:03:41.470 align:middle line:90%


00:03:41.470 --> 00:03:42.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:42.640 --> 00:03:47.230 align:middle line:84%
And so if you do take k
steps of the random walk,

00:03:47.230 --> 00:03:49.670 align:middle line:84%
then there will be some
probability distribution

00:03:49.670 --> 00:03:52.030 align:middle line:84%
of where you end
up after k steps.

00:03:52.030 --> 00:03:55.760 align:middle line:84%
And one main question
about random walks

00:03:55.760 --> 00:03:59.060 align:middle line:84%
is, how evenly distributed is
that probability distribution?

00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:01.720 align:middle line:90%


00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:13.320 align:middle line:84%
So question-- how
evenly distributed

00:04:13.320 --> 00:04:16.389 align:middle line:84%
is the random walk
after k steps?

00:04:16.389 --> 00:04:20.920 align:middle line:90%


00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:23.030 align:middle line:84%
And we'll make this more
precise in a moment.

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:26.160 align:middle line:90%


00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:27.000 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:35.000 align:middle line:84%
So it is helpful to describe
this random walk using

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:36.020 align:middle line:90%
convolution.

00:04:36.020 --> 00:04:45.660 align:middle line:90%


00:04:45.660 --> 00:04:46.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:48.740 align:middle line:84%
So convolution on a
group looks like this.

00:04:48.740 --> 00:04:52.080 align:middle line:84%
We have two functions,
f1 and f2, on this group.

00:04:52.080 --> 00:04:56.550 align:middle line:84%
And then if I convolve
them with each other

00:04:56.550 --> 00:05:00.410 align:middle line:84%
and I evaluate that
at g, that's the sum

00:05:00.410 --> 00:05:09.330 align:middle line:84%
g1 times g2 equals g f of
g1, f1 of g1, f2 of g2.

00:05:09.330 --> 00:05:11.490 align:middle line:84%
That's the sum over
all the g1 and g2

00:05:11.490 --> 00:05:13.630 align:middle line:90%
that multiply to g of this.

00:05:13.630 --> 00:05:17.330 align:middle line:90%


00:05:17.330 --> 00:05:19.495 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:19.495 --> 00:05:22.850 align:middle line:84%
And then for mu, we
can make an operator.

00:05:22.850 --> 00:05:27.250 align:middle line:84%
And T mu of f is just
f convolved with mu.

00:05:27.250 --> 00:05:31.850 align:middle line:84%
And this operator basically
describes this random walk.

00:05:31.850 --> 00:05:34.130 align:middle line:84%
So let's say how
they're related.

00:05:34.130 --> 00:05:37.530 align:middle line:84%
So suppose I were to
take T mu and apply it

00:05:37.530 --> 00:05:42.510 align:middle line:84%
to the delta function at g0
and evaluate that at some g.

00:05:42.510 --> 00:05:45.970 align:middle line:90%


00:05:45.970 --> 00:05:46.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:46.470 --> 00:05:47.970 align:middle line:90%
So let's see.

00:05:47.970 --> 00:05:51.780 align:middle line:90%
What's a good way to write this?

00:05:51.780 --> 00:05:55.257 align:middle line:84%
So that's the sum
of-- actually, let

00:05:55.257 --> 00:05:56.840 align:middle line:84%
me look at how I
wrote it in my notes.

00:05:56.840 --> 00:05:58.632 align:middle line:84%
I tried writing this
a few ways, and then I

00:05:58.632 --> 00:06:00.360 align:middle line:84%
decided there was a
good way to write it.

00:06:00.360 --> 00:06:03.360 align:middle line:90%


00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:04.120 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:05.200 align:middle line:90%
Let's write it this way.

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:07.820 align:middle line:90%


00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:11.940 align:middle line:84%
So suppose I want to
evaluate this at g0 times h.

00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:15.740 align:middle line:84%
So that's the sum
over g1 times g2

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:19.900 align:middle line:84%
equals g0 times h
of delta function

00:06:19.900 --> 00:06:26.460 align:middle line:90%
at g0 of g1 times mu of g2.

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:27.260 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:30.700 align:middle line:84%
So the only way that this sum
can be not 0 is if g1 is g0.

00:06:30.700 --> 00:06:33.460 align:middle line:90%


00:06:33.460 --> 00:06:36.580 align:middle line:84%
So there's only one
term in this sum.

00:06:36.580 --> 00:06:44.980 align:middle line:84%
That's this g0 times g2
is g0 times h of mu of g2.

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:47.640 align:middle line:84%
There's only one term, and
it's the term where g2 is h.

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:52.310 align:middle line:90%


00:06:52.310 --> 00:06:53.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:53.070 --> 00:06:56.550 align:middle line:84%
So this thing is the
probability distribution

00:06:56.550 --> 00:06:58.210 align:middle line:90%
of one step of the random walk.

00:06:58.210 --> 00:07:02.310 align:middle line:84%
The probability if I started at
g0 that I end up at g0 times h

00:07:02.310 --> 00:07:03.310 align:middle line:90%
is mu of h.

00:07:03.310 --> 00:07:05.350 align:middle line:84%
That's the definition
of my random walk.

00:07:05.350 --> 00:07:09.310 align:middle line:84%
So this operator is performing
one step of the random walk.

00:07:09.310 --> 00:07:14.630 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, if I take
T mu to the k of delta g0,

00:07:14.630 --> 00:07:20.940 align:middle line:84%
that's like k steps of the
random walk, starting at g0.

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:28.970 align:middle line:90%


00:07:28.970 --> 00:07:29.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:29.470 --> 00:07:35.325 align:middle line:90%


00:07:35.325 --> 00:07:36.450 align:middle line:90%
Actually, let me say this--

00:07:36.450 --> 00:07:37.490 align:middle line:90%
I could say this better.

00:07:37.490 --> 00:07:40.110 align:middle line:90%


00:07:40.110 --> 00:07:45.470 align:middle line:84%
So this is the probability
that our random walk

00:07:45.470 --> 00:07:50.610 align:middle line:90%
is at g after k steps.

00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:55.380 align:middle line:90%


00:07:55.380 --> 00:07:55.880 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:58.360 align:middle line:84%
Now we can take this question,
how evenly distributed

00:07:58.360 --> 00:07:59.420 align:middle line:90%
is the random walk?

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:02.000 align:middle line:84%
We can write that as a
precise question about this.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.260 align:middle line:90%
I'll call it question 1.

00:08:03.260 --> 00:08:05.920 align:middle line:90%


00:08:05.920 --> 00:08:14.960 align:middle line:84%
So I'd like to estimate T
mu to the k of delta g0.

00:08:14.960 --> 00:08:17.580 align:middle line:84%
So this is the actual
probability distribution.

00:08:17.580 --> 00:08:19.840 align:middle line:84%
And if the probability
was completely even

00:08:19.840 --> 00:08:23.240 align:middle line:84%
over the whole group, it would
be 1 over the size of the group

00:08:23.240 --> 00:08:24.200 align:middle line:90%
everywhere.

00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:27.840 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to see how close
it is to that by measuring

00:08:27.840 --> 00:08:30.040 align:middle line:90%
the norm of this difference.

00:08:30.040 --> 00:08:31.720 align:middle line:90%
So I'd like to estimate that.

00:08:31.720 --> 00:08:32.220 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:36.179 align:middle line:84%
And L2 is helpful but also
perhaps a little arbitrary.

00:08:36.179 --> 00:08:39.000 align:middle line:84%
You could also put other
norms, so could put

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.340 align:middle line:84%
or L infinity or
maybe some other norm.

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:47.650 align:middle line:90%


00:08:47.650 --> 00:08:48.250 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:48.250 --> 00:08:50.770 align:middle line:84%
So this is the kind of question
about random walks on groups

00:08:50.770 --> 00:08:54.610 align:middle line:84%
that we are going to
try to understand.

00:08:54.610 --> 00:08:56.010 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:08:56.010 --> 00:08:59.330 align:middle line:84%
So to understand this,
it is helpful to notice

00:08:59.330 --> 00:09:01.530 align:middle line:90%
that this is a linear operator.

00:09:01.530 --> 00:09:03.230 align:middle line:90%
This T mu is a linear operator.

00:09:03.230 --> 00:09:04.730 align:middle line:90%
It's basically a matrix.

00:09:04.730 --> 00:09:08.670 align:middle line:84%
And it's helpful to think about
that in terms of matrix ideas,

00:09:08.670 --> 00:09:11.540 align:middle line:84%
like the singular values and
singular vectors of this matrix.

00:09:11.540 --> 00:09:15.370 align:middle line:90%


00:09:15.370 --> 00:09:21.490 align:middle line:90%
So T mu is a linear operator.

00:09:21.490 --> 00:09:26.890 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to study the
singular values and singular

00:09:26.890 --> 00:09:32.850 align:middle line:90%
vectors of T. OK.

00:09:32.850 --> 00:09:40.370 align:middle line:84%
So there is one simple singular
value or eigenvalue, I guess,

00:09:40.370 --> 00:09:44.090 align:middle line:90%
that T mu of 1 is 1.

00:09:44.090 --> 00:09:44.837 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:09:44.837 --> 00:09:47.420 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Are singular values
and single vectors just the same

00:09:47.420 --> 00:09:51.100 align:middle line:84%
as eigenvalues and
eigenvectors [INAUDIBLE]?

00:09:51.100 --> 00:09:54.580 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: They
are closely related.

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:59.000 align:middle line:84%
So let me do a quick review of
singular values and eigenvalues.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:05.010 align:middle line:90%


00:10:05.010 --> 00:10:05.510 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:10:05.510 --> 00:10:09.420 align:middle line:90%


00:10:09.420 --> 00:10:12.060 align:middle line:84%
If you have a
matrix and you think

00:10:12.060 --> 00:10:15.340 align:middle line:84%
about what it does
to the unit ball,

00:10:15.340 --> 00:10:20.980 align:middle line:84%
it will turn the unit
ball into an ellipsoid.

00:10:20.980 --> 00:10:24.060 align:middle line:84%
And the principal
axes of this ellipsoid

00:10:24.060 --> 00:10:30.718 align:middle line:84%
are the singular values,
sigma 1, sigma 2.

00:10:30.718 --> 00:10:34.786 align:middle line:90%


00:10:34.786 --> 00:10:35.286 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:35.286 --> 00:10:46.760 align:middle line:90%


00:10:46.760 --> 00:10:49.470 align:middle line:84%
So if we look at the
preimages of these things,

00:10:49.470 --> 00:10:50.970 align:middle line:84%
those will be the
singular vectors--

00:10:50.970 --> 00:10:54.200 align:middle line:90%


00:10:54.200 --> 00:10:55.720 align:middle line:84%
well, depending on
the matrix, they

00:10:55.720 --> 00:10:57.840 align:middle line:90%
could be pointing any which way.

00:10:57.840 --> 00:11:06.160 align:middle line:84%
But maybe that's
v2 and that is v1.

00:11:06.160 --> 00:11:06.660 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:06.660 --> 00:11:09.120 align:middle line:90%
And they will always be--

00:11:09.120 --> 00:11:25.840 align:middle line:84%
so we'll have-- so the Vi, or
orthonormal, and the size of MVi

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:27.260 align:middle line:90%
is sigma i.

00:11:27.260 --> 00:11:30.640 align:middle line:90%


00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:34.380 align:middle line:84%
And the MVi are also
orthonormal also orthogonal.

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:37.320 align:middle line:90%


00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:38.690 align:middle line:90%
Those are the singular vectors.

00:11:38.690 --> 00:11:43.270 align:middle line:90%


00:11:43.270 --> 00:11:43.770 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:43.770 --> 00:11:47.650 align:middle line:84%
Now, they are not
generally eigenvectors,

00:11:47.650 --> 00:11:53.570 align:middle line:84%
in the sense that MVi will not
usually be a multiple of Vi.

00:11:53.570 --> 00:11:56.610 align:middle line:84%
But they are closely
related to them.

00:11:56.610 --> 00:12:06.990 align:middle line:84%
The Vi are the eigenvectors of
M M star-- or M star M, I guess.

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:09.570 align:middle line:90%


00:12:09.570 --> 00:12:17.706 align:middle line:84%
And the sigma i squared are
the eigenvalues of M star M

00:12:17.706 --> 00:12:19.840 align:middle line:90%
equal to lamda i M M star.

00:12:19.840 --> 00:12:27.090 align:middle line:90%


00:12:27.090 --> 00:12:31.330 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, this
biggest singular vector

00:12:31.330 --> 00:12:36.690 align:middle line:84%
measures the operator norm
of the matrix, which is the--

00:12:36.690 --> 00:12:38.810 align:middle line:90%
so these are ordered like this.

00:12:38.810 --> 00:12:54.824 align:middle line:90%
And Mv is at most sigma 1 v.

00:12:54.824 --> 00:12:56.152 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:56.152 --> 00:12:58.340 align:middle line:84%
So the reason we're talking
about singular values

00:12:58.340 --> 00:13:01.300 align:middle line:84%
is, we're going to care
about stuff like this.

00:13:01.300 --> 00:13:05.520 align:middle line:84%
And this is naturally
associated with singular values

00:13:05.520 --> 00:13:06.720 align:middle line:90%
if M is not symmetric.

00:13:06.720 --> 00:13:09.280 align:middle line:84%
It's not necessarily the same
as talking about eigenvalues.

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:20.620 align:middle line:90%


00:13:20.620 --> 00:13:21.120 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:23.780 align:middle line:84%
So if we take this
T mu of the function

00:13:23.780 --> 00:13:26.620 align:middle line:84%
1, the constant function,
we will just get 1.

00:13:26.620 --> 00:13:31.260 align:middle line:84%
Because this T mu is like
an averaging operator.

00:13:31.260 --> 00:13:34.540 align:middle line:84%
We're averaging T--
so T mu of f at g

00:13:34.540 --> 00:13:39.870 align:middle line:84%
is the average value of g at
some other places around g

00:13:39.870 --> 00:13:41.670 align:middle line:90%
that are dictated by mu.

00:13:41.670 --> 00:13:43.210 align:middle line:90%
So T mu of 1 is 1.

00:13:43.210 --> 00:13:50.110 align:middle line:90%


00:13:50.110 --> 00:13:54.350 align:middle line:90%
So that implies that the--

00:13:54.350 --> 00:13:54.850 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:54.850 --> 00:13:58.430 align:middle line:90%
So I'll do a little lemma.

00:13:58.430 --> 00:13:59.990 align:middle line:90%
The largest singular value--

00:13:59.990 --> 00:14:04.750 align:middle line:90%


00:14:04.750 --> 00:14:05.330 align:middle line:90%
yeah, OK.

00:14:05.330 --> 00:14:07.350 align:middle line:90%
So little lemma is that.

00:14:07.350 --> 00:14:11.750 align:middle line:84%
T mu of f in L2 is
at most f in L2.

00:14:11.750 --> 00:14:17.070 align:middle line:84%
And this is sharp
because of this example.

00:14:17.070 --> 00:14:17.870 align:middle line:90%
It could be equal.

00:14:17.870 --> 00:14:23.370 align:middle line:90%


00:14:23.370 --> 00:14:23.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:23.870 --> 00:14:26.190 align:middle line:84%
So proving this will help
us think a little bit

00:14:26.190 --> 00:14:28.670 align:middle line:90%
about what convolution means.

00:14:28.670 --> 00:14:35.490 align:middle line:84%
So T mu of f is f
convolved with mu--

00:14:35.490 --> 00:14:38.030 align:middle line:90%
g here.

00:14:38.030 --> 00:14:46.920 align:middle line:84%
So that's the sum g1 g2
equals g f of g1 mu of g2.

00:14:46.920 --> 00:14:49.760 align:middle line:84%
And I'd like to think of
this as a sum over g2.

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:52.360 align:middle line:90%
So it's the sum over g2.

00:14:52.360 --> 00:14:56.080 align:middle line:84%
Because I'm thinking of it that
way, I can bring the mu of g2

00:14:56.080 --> 00:14:57.240 align:middle line:90%
out front.

00:14:57.240 --> 00:15:01.220 align:middle line:84%
And then what I have
left is f of g1,

00:15:01.220 --> 00:15:03.610 align:middle line:90%
which is g times g2 inverse.

00:15:03.610 --> 00:15:06.480 align:middle line:90%


00:15:06.480 --> 00:15:10.640 align:middle line:84%
And I want to think of this as
a linear combination of a bunch

00:15:10.640 --> 00:15:14.400 align:middle line:90%
of different functions of g.

00:15:14.400 --> 00:15:14.900 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:16.240 align:middle line:90%
Let's give them a name.

00:15:16.240 --> 00:15:19.520 align:middle line:84%
So this function
of g is sort of f.

00:15:19.520 --> 00:15:21.260 align:middle line:90%
But we first did this thing.

00:15:21.260 --> 00:15:23.200 align:middle line:84%
And I want you to
think of it as taking f

00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:26.400 align:middle line:84%
and then shifting
it using the group.

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:30.880 align:middle line:84%
So it's the right
translation by g2 of f of g

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:35.160 align:middle line:84%
is defined to be
this thing here.

00:15:35.160 --> 00:15:38.450 align:middle line:90%
So we could plug that in.

00:15:38.450 --> 00:15:43.290 align:middle line:84%
And this shifting operation
doesn't change the norm of g.

00:15:43.290 --> 00:15:50.360 align:middle line:84%
So Rg2 of f in L2 is
the same as f in L2.

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:52.090 align:middle line:90%
Ah, I've been mentioning L2.

00:15:52.090 --> 00:15:55.190 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, I should say--

00:15:55.190 --> 00:15:55.690 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:55.690 --> 00:15:56.830 align:middle line:90%
Let me pause for a second.

00:15:56.830 --> 00:15:58.420 align:middle line:84%
I should have said
something before.

00:15:58.420 --> 00:16:04.290 align:middle line:90%


00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:05.890 align:middle line:84%
So when we have
these functions on g,

00:16:05.890 --> 00:16:08.610 align:middle line:84%
we're going to
measure their norm.

00:16:08.610 --> 00:16:15.823 align:middle line:84%
And if I have f L2 of g, this
is going to be sum g of g?

00:16:15.823 --> 00:16:20.090 align:middle line:90%
F of g squared to the 1/2.

00:16:20.090 --> 00:16:22.170 align:middle line:90%
Or I could take inner product.

00:16:22.170 --> 00:16:28.570 align:middle line:84%
The inner product of f1
and f2 is the sum g of G f1

00:16:28.570 --> 00:16:31.630 align:middle line:90%
of g, f2 of g to that.

00:16:31.630 --> 00:16:33.650 align:middle line:84%
So the functions on
G are a Hilbert space

00:16:33.650 --> 00:16:35.460 align:middle line:90%
with this natural measure.

00:16:35.460 --> 00:16:36.240 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:41.740 align:middle line:84%
So then if I take a function
and I translate it or do

00:16:41.740 --> 00:16:44.960 align:middle line:84%
this right translation,
that just permutes the value

00:16:44.960 --> 00:16:46.860 align:middle line:90%
so it doesn't change this thing.

00:16:46.860 --> 00:16:47.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:47.860 --> 00:16:56.850 align:middle line:84%
So now if we look at our
T mu of f, I have this--

00:16:56.850 --> 00:17:00.520 align:middle line:90%


00:17:00.520 --> 00:17:01.020 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:17:01.020 --> 00:17:14.780 align:middle line:84%
So actually, if I'm interested
in the norm of T mu of f,

00:17:14.780 --> 00:17:24.060 align:middle line:84%
this is the norm of the sum
on g2 mu of g2 R sub g2 of f.

00:17:24.060 --> 00:17:26.920 align:middle line:84%
It's a linear combination
of these functions,

00:17:26.920 --> 00:17:29.380 align:middle line:90%
which are all translates of f.

00:17:29.380 --> 00:17:30.760 align:middle line:90%
And L2 is a norm.

00:17:30.760 --> 00:17:32.600 align:middle line:84%
It obeys the
triangle inequality.

00:17:32.600 --> 00:17:40.510 align:middle line:84%
So this is less than the sum on
g2, mu of g2, Rg2 of f in L2.

00:17:40.510 --> 00:17:48.810 align:middle line:84%
All of these have the same
norm, which is the L2 norm of f

00:17:48.810 --> 00:17:50.630 align:middle line:90%
And then this adds up to 1.

00:17:50.630 --> 00:17:52.650 align:middle line:84%
So this is just
the L2 norm of f.

00:17:52.650 --> 00:17:56.430 align:middle line:90%


00:17:56.430 --> 00:17:58.560 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:17:58.560 --> 00:18:03.510 align:middle line:84%
So this is a basic fact
about averaging operators.

00:18:03.510 --> 00:18:08.230 align:middle line:84%
And to understand whether the
random walk is mixing things up,

00:18:08.230 --> 00:18:12.430 align:middle line:84%
we have to care about how it
behaves on the space orthogonal

00:18:12.430 --> 00:18:13.510 align:middle line:90%
to 1.

00:18:13.510 --> 00:18:16.030 align:middle line:84%
And the first observation is
that it preserves the space

00:18:16.030 --> 00:18:17.590 align:middle line:90%
orthogonal to 1.

00:18:17.590 --> 00:18:21.710 align:middle line:84%
So let's give that space
a name, say L2 of G 0

00:18:21.710 --> 00:18:30.910 align:middle line:84%
is the set of f and L2 of g so
that some g in G of f of g is 0.

00:18:30.910 --> 00:18:32.520 align:middle line:84%
This is saying that
f is orthogonal

00:18:32.520 --> 00:18:35.240 align:middle line:90%
to the constant function.

00:18:35.240 --> 00:18:35.986 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:35.986 --> 00:18:41.240 align:middle line:84%
So another simple lemma is
that our operator T mu actually

00:18:41.240 --> 00:18:45.120 align:middle line:90%
takes this space to itself.

00:18:45.120 --> 00:18:47.060 align:middle line:84%
So it takes the constant
function to itself,

00:18:47.060 --> 00:18:48.600 align:middle line:84%
and it takes the
perpendicular space

00:18:48.600 --> 00:18:51.640 align:middle line:84%
to itself, which will imply
that the constant function is

00:18:51.640 --> 00:18:55.800 align:middle line:84%
one of the singular
vectors of this operator.

00:18:55.800 --> 00:19:07.280 align:middle line:84%
OK, so proof-- so I want to
understand the sum g in G T

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:09.000 align:middle line:90%
mu f of g.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.140 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to imagine that
the sum of f of g is 0,

00:19:11.140 --> 00:19:13.520 align:middle line:84%
and I want to see if
that's still true.

00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:14.400 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:19:14.400 --> 00:19:19.000 align:middle line:84%
So that's the sum g
in G. Sum g1 times g2

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:24.360 align:middle line:90%
equals g, f of g1 mu of g2.

00:19:24.360 --> 00:19:26.760 align:middle line:84%
And if you think about
what we're summing over,

00:19:26.760 --> 00:19:30.440 align:middle line:84%
we're just summing
over g1 and g2.

00:19:30.440 --> 00:19:37.650 align:middle line:84%
So this is the sum over g1
and g2, of f of g1, mu of G2.

00:19:37.650 --> 00:19:38.720 align:middle line:90%
And now that factors.

00:19:38.720 --> 00:19:47.770 align:middle line:90%


00:19:47.770 --> 00:19:48.910 align:middle line:90%
So this is 1.

00:19:48.910 --> 00:19:51.520 align:middle line:84%
And if f was in L2 of
G 0, this would be 0.

00:19:51.520 --> 00:19:56.250 align:middle line:90%


00:19:56.250 --> 00:19:59.130 align:middle line:90%
This is 0.

00:19:59.130 --> 00:20:04.650 align:middle line:84%
So if f is in L2 of G 0, then
so T mu of f will be also.

00:20:04.650 --> 00:20:05.510 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:20:05.510 --> 00:20:31.300 align:middle line:90%


00:20:31.300 --> 00:20:32.140 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:20:32.140 --> 00:20:38.780 align:middle line:84%
So we've seen that
T mu of 1 is 1.

00:20:38.780 --> 00:20:43.820 align:middle line:84%
And T mu takes L2
of G 0 to itself.

00:20:43.820 --> 00:20:46.940 align:middle line:84%
So this is the largest
singular value.

00:20:46.940 --> 00:20:47.760 align:middle line:90%
So we've seen it.

00:20:47.760 --> 00:20:50.900 align:middle line:84%
And then here, there's
something else.

00:20:50.900 --> 00:20:54.580 align:middle line:90%
So let's say sigma 1 of mu--

00:20:54.580 --> 00:20:56.420 align:middle line:90%
so this is 1.

00:20:56.420 --> 00:20:58.860 align:middle line:90%
I'll call it sigma 0 of T mu.

00:20:58.860 --> 00:21:01.040 align:middle line:84%
Somehow, in this setting,
the 1 is trivial.

00:21:01.040 --> 00:21:03.180 align:middle line:84%
And everything else will
depend on the trace of mu.

00:21:03.180 --> 00:21:10.870 align:middle line:84%
So sigma 1 of T mu is the
largest singular value

00:21:10.870 --> 00:21:14.460 align:middle line:90%
of this part.

00:21:14.460 --> 00:21:16.180 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:16.180 --> 00:21:17.420 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:21:17.420 --> 00:21:25.620 align:middle line:84%
So question 2 is going to
be to estimate sigma 1 of t.

00:21:25.620 --> 00:21:28.870 align:middle line:84%
And these two questions
are related to each other.

00:21:28.870 --> 00:21:33.830 align:middle line:84%
This thing helps
to understand how--

00:21:33.830 --> 00:21:36.530 align:middle line:84%
it helps a lot to understand
how this operator behaves

00:21:36.530 --> 00:21:39.030 align:middle line:90%
and to answer question 1.

00:21:39.030 --> 00:21:41.990 align:middle line:84%
So let me put up a simple
proposition, how question 2 is

00:21:41.990 --> 00:21:44.550 align:middle line:90%
related to question 1.

00:21:44.550 --> 00:21:50.710 align:middle line:84%
So proposition-- if you look at
that thing, T mu to the k delta

00:21:50.710 --> 00:21:55.030 align:middle line:84%
function of g0 minus
1 over G in L2,

00:21:55.030 --> 00:22:00.890 align:middle line:84%
this is bounded by sigma
1 of T mu to the k.

00:22:00.890 --> 00:22:04.310 align:middle line:90%


00:22:04.310 --> 00:22:09.910 align:middle line:84%
OK, so proof-- so we want
to see what T mu to the k

00:22:09.910 --> 00:22:13.350 align:middle line:84%
does to a delta
function at a point.

00:22:13.350 --> 00:22:15.910 align:middle line:84%
Let's take this delta
function at a point.

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:19.070 align:middle line:90%
And T mu splits up.

00:22:19.070 --> 00:22:21.470 align:middle line:84%
The constant function is
an eigenfunction and then

00:22:21.470 --> 00:22:23.510 align:middle line:90%
the things with mean 0.

00:22:23.510 --> 00:22:26.560 align:middle line:84%
So let's split up
this delta function.

00:22:26.560 --> 00:22:31.760 align:middle line:84%
So the constant part
of it is like this.

00:22:31.760 --> 00:22:36.480 align:middle line:90%
And then we have this.

00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:38.520 align:middle line:84%
So the reason we
split it up that way

00:22:38.520 --> 00:22:41.640 align:middle line:84%
is that this part, which in
the beginning of the class,

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:45.160 align:middle line:84%
we would have called
the high part of this--

00:22:45.160 --> 00:22:47.480 align:middle line:90%
so I guess I'll do that.

00:22:47.480 --> 00:22:51.360 align:middle line:90%
That's in L2 of G 0.

00:22:51.360 --> 00:22:52.920 align:middle line:90%
The 0 part.

00:22:52.920 --> 00:22:53.420 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:53.420 --> 00:22:55.760 align:middle line:84%
Now what happens when
we apply this operator?

00:22:55.760 --> 00:23:00.240 align:middle line:84%
Well, this operator takes
constants to constants.

00:23:00.240 --> 00:23:03.600 align:middle line:84%
It's the identity on
the constant part.

00:23:03.600 --> 00:23:10.080 align:middle line:84%
And so if I take T
mu to the k delta g0,

00:23:10.080 --> 00:23:14.560 align:middle line:84%
this part will stay
1 over G inside.

00:23:14.560 --> 00:23:15.780 align:middle line:90%
I'll take the left-hand side.

00:23:15.780 --> 00:23:17.900 align:middle line:84%
And then if I subtract
that, it will disappear.

00:23:17.900 --> 00:23:19.840 align:middle line:84%
So what I'll be
left with is T mu

00:23:19.840 --> 00:23:27.630 align:middle line:84%
to the k on this high
part of the delta g0.

00:23:27.630 --> 00:23:28.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:23:28.130 --> 00:23:29.230 align:middle line:90%
How big is that?

00:23:29.230 --> 00:23:32.050 align:middle line:84%
Well, this part
lives in this space.

00:23:32.050 --> 00:23:36.560 align:middle line:84%
So we can bound the size of this
thing using the singular vector.

00:23:36.560 --> 00:23:41.610 align:middle line:90%


00:23:41.610 --> 00:23:50.650 align:middle line:84%
So we get T mu to the
k of delta g0 high to--

00:23:50.650 --> 00:24:01.480 align:middle line:84%
that's bounded by sigma 1 of T
mu to k times delta g0 high L2.

00:24:01.480 --> 00:24:07.050 align:middle line:90%


00:24:07.050 --> 00:24:07.550 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:07.550 --> 00:24:10.090 align:middle line:84%
And now it's also now
straightforward to check

00:24:10.090 --> 00:24:11.550 align:middle line:90%
that this is smaller than 1.

00:24:11.550 --> 00:24:26.580 align:middle line:90%


00:24:26.580 --> 00:24:29.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:29.020 --> 00:24:34.820 align:middle line:90%
So it's an application.

00:24:34.820 --> 00:24:40.140 align:middle line:84%
If we were able to arrange
that sigma 1 of T mu to the k

00:24:40.140 --> 00:24:47.060 align:middle line:84%
was less than 1 over 100
times the size of G, then,

00:24:47.060 --> 00:24:50.380 align:middle line:84%
well, this L2 norm would be less
than 1 over 100 times the size

00:24:50.380 --> 00:24:51.420 align:middle line:90%
of G.

00:24:51.420 --> 00:24:53.700 align:middle line:84%
And so in particular,
the L infinity norm

00:24:53.700 --> 00:24:57.180 align:middle line:84%
would be less than 1 over
100 times the size of G.

00:24:57.180 --> 00:25:02.380 align:middle line:84%
So then I would say
that for every G,

00:25:02.380 --> 00:25:09.140 align:middle line:84%
T mu k delta g0 of g
minus 1 over the size of g

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:12.948 align:middle line:84%
would be smaller than 1 over
100 times the size of g.

00:25:12.948 --> 00:25:14.740 align:middle line:84%
That would tell us,
say, that this function

00:25:14.740 --> 00:25:18.540 align:middle line:84%
is pretty close to this
constant function, within 1%.

00:25:18.540 --> 00:25:24.670 align:middle line:84%
So that random walk would now
have mixed pretty thoroughly.

00:25:24.670 --> 00:25:25.870 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

00:25:25.870 --> 00:25:30.430 align:middle line:84%
So if we can get our
hands on sigma 1 of T mu,

00:25:30.430 --> 00:25:34.230 align:middle line:84%
then we can figure out how
long it takes this random walk

00:25:34.230 --> 00:25:35.140 align:middle line:90%
to mix evenly.

00:25:35.140 --> 00:25:39.570 align:middle line:90%


00:25:39.570 --> 00:25:40.070 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:25:40.070 --> 00:25:50.750 align:middle line:90%


00:25:50.750 --> 00:25:52.710 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:52.710 --> 00:25:56.070 align:middle line:84%
So now let me tell you
an interesting example

00:25:56.070 --> 00:25:58.550 align:middle line:84%
of a particular group
and a particular mu

00:25:58.550 --> 00:26:00.490 align:middle line:84%
where there's a cool
estimate for this.

00:26:00.490 --> 00:26:23.800 align:middle line:90%


00:26:23.800 --> 00:26:26.480 align:middle line:84%
So we are going
to mostly focus--

00:26:26.480 --> 00:26:30.390 align:middle line:84%
or maybe only focus--
on the group SL2 of Fp--

00:26:30.390 --> 00:26:33.400 align:middle line:90%


00:26:33.400 --> 00:26:38.460 align:middle line:84%
and could pick many different
measures for a random walk.

00:26:38.460 --> 00:26:40.960 align:middle line:84%
But one nice one
which has been studied

00:26:40.960 --> 00:26:46.160 align:middle line:84%
is to take the set A to
be-- so, first of all,

00:26:46.160 --> 00:26:49.440 align:middle line:84%
if A is a subset of g,
there's a natural measure

00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:52.920 align:middle line:84%
on A, which is the uniform
measure, so measure on A,

00:26:52.920 --> 00:26:55.920 align:middle line:84%
which is 1 over the
cardinality of A times

00:26:55.920 --> 00:27:02.320 align:middle line:90%
the sum a in A of delta A.

00:27:02.320 --> 00:27:02.820 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:02.820 --> 00:27:06.020 align:middle line:84%
So there's a nice set,
A, inside of here,

00:27:06.020 --> 00:27:08.290 align:middle line:84%
which was studied by
Selberg, A. Selberg.

00:27:08.290 --> 00:27:12.800 align:middle line:90%


00:27:12.800 --> 00:27:15.060 align:middle line:84%
Well, OK, which is relevant
to a theorem of Selberg.

00:27:15.060 --> 00:27:16.840 align:middle line:90%
He set his theorem differently.

00:27:16.840 --> 00:27:21.410 align:middle line:90%


00:27:21.410 --> 00:27:22.050 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:22.050 --> 00:27:25.210 align:middle line:84%
So there are four
elements in this set.

00:27:25.210 --> 00:27:28.430 align:middle line:84%
And these are our generators
of the group SL2 Fp.

00:27:28.430 --> 00:27:29.930 align:middle line:84%
There are many ways
you could choose

00:27:29.930 --> 00:27:31.610 align:middle line:84%
generators for this group,
but this is probably

00:27:31.610 --> 00:27:32.590 align:middle line:90%
the simplest way.

00:27:32.590 --> 00:27:36.850 align:middle line:90%


00:27:36.850 --> 00:27:37.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:37.350 --> 00:27:39.810 align:middle line:90%
And now I can state a theorem.

00:27:39.810 --> 00:27:43.690 align:middle line:84%
So theorem 1 exists
a positive c--

00:27:43.690 --> 00:27:46.850 align:middle line:84%
I think 1 over 100
should be fine--

00:27:46.850 --> 00:27:51.810 align:middle line:84%
so that for every
p prime, if you

00:27:51.810 --> 00:27:57.130 align:middle line:90%
take A Selberg and SL2 of Fp.

00:27:57.130 --> 00:27:59.530 align:middle line:90%
You make a random walk.

00:27:59.530 --> 00:28:06.210 align:middle line:84%
So in this setting, let me
write TA for T sub mu sub A.

00:28:06.210 --> 00:28:11.490 align:middle line:84%
Then sigma 1 of
TA is less than 1

00:28:11.490 --> 00:28:14.560 align:middle line:84%
minus c, so uniformly
for all primes.

00:28:14.560 --> 00:28:22.780 align:middle line:90%


00:28:22.780 --> 00:28:25.140 align:middle line:90%
So this is, say, 99/100.

00:28:25.140 --> 00:28:30.300 align:middle line:84%
Then you can just read
off high powers of this

00:28:30.300 --> 00:28:31.400 align:middle line:90%
or bounded by something.

00:28:31.400 --> 00:28:34.340 align:middle line:84%
And you can plug that into
the discussion over here.

00:28:34.340 --> 00:28:38.220 align:middle line:84%
So it says that that random
walk mixes extremely fast.

00:28:38.220 --> 00:28:38.740 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:28:38.740 --> 00:28:40.420 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: How does
sigma 1 behave

00:28:40.420 --> 00:28:42.200 align:middle line:90%
as you iterate over the primes?

00:28:42.200 --> 00:28:48.100 align:middle line:84%
Does it converge to sub 1
minus c or oscillate a lot ?

00:28:48.100 --> 00:28:50.860 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So the question
is, how does sigma 1 of to

00:28:50.860 --> 00:28:55.780 align:middle line:90%
behave as the prime varies?

00:28:55.780 --> 00:28:57.850 align:middle line:84%
I do not know the
answer to that question.

00:28:57.850 --> 00:29:03.060 align:middle line:90%


00:29:03.060 --> 00:29:09.020 align:middle line:84%
So let me say that this is
a corollary of a theorem

00:29:09.020 --> 00:29:13.610 align:middle line:90%
of Selberg from the late '50s.

00:29:13.610 --> 00:29:17.910 align:middle line:90%


00:29:17.910 --> 00:29:22.150 align:middle line:84%
And Selberg's actual theorem
is about the first eigenvalue

00:29:22.150 --> 00:29:25.990 align:middle line:84%
of the Laplacian on a
hyperbolic surface, which

00:29:25.990 --> 00:29:29.270 align:middle line:90%
is associated to this group.

00:29:29.270 --> 00:29:30.710 align:middle line:90%
And you can go back and forth.

00:29:30.710 --> 00:29:32.710 align:middle line:84%
With modern technology,
it's considered not very

00:29:32.710 --> 00:29:34.950 align:middle line:84%
difficult to go back and
forth between a bound

00:29:34.950 --> 00:29:38.513 align:middle line:84%
for the eigenvalue of the
surface and a bound here.

00:29:38.513 --> 00:29:39.930 align:middle line:84%
But when you do
go back and forth,

00:29:39.930 --> 00:29:43.310 align:middle line:90%
you will screw up the constants.

00:29:43.310 --> 00:29:47.270 align:middle line:84%
Selberg's theorem was that the
first eigenvalue of that surface

00:29:47.270 --> 00:29:50.270 align:middle line:90%
was at least 3/16.

00:29:50.270 --> 00:29:52.210 align:middle line:84%
And that's probably
not the right answer.

00:29:52.210 --> 00:29:55.470 align:middle line:84%
And he conjectured that
it should be a quarter.

00:29:55.470 --> 00:29:59.350 align:middle line:84%
So for his actual problem,
there is a beautiful conjecture

00:29:59.350 --> 00:30:01.410 align:middle line:84%
about what happens as
p goes to infinity,

00:30:01.410 --> 00:30:06.710 align:middle line:84%
which is that the eigenvalues
should converge to a quarter.

00:30:06.710 --> 00:30:08.010 align:middle line:90%
For this, I'm not sure.

00:30:08.010 --> 00:30:13.310 align:middle line:90%


00:30:13.310 --> 00:30:14.280 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:30:14.280 --> 00:30:17.890 align:middle line:90%


00:30:17.890 --> 00:30:19.210 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:30:19.210 --> 00:30:20.170 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:20.170 --> 00:30:24.650 align:middle line:84%
So bounds like this are
also related to expander

00:30:24.650 --> 00:30:27.930 align:middle line:84%
graphs, isoperimetric
inequalities in graphs.

00:30:27.930 --> 00:30:30.770 align:middle line:84%
And I thought I
would also show that.

00:30:30.770 --> 00:30:33.210 align:middle line:90%
And so it shows that--

00:30:33.210 --> 00:30:35.430 align:middle line:84%
well, OK, so let
me explain that.

00:30:35.430 --> 00:30:39.590 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a set of
generators inside of a group,

00:30:39.590 --> 00:30:41.840 align:middle line:84%
we can use that to make a
graph called a Cayley graph.

00:30:41.840 --> 00:30:44.490 align:middle line:90%


00:30:44.490 --> 00:30:48.850 align:middle line:84%
And this mixing inequality
can be thought of

00:30:48.850 --> 00:30:52.020 align:middle line:84%
or implies some interesting
geometric features of the graph.

00:30:52.020 --> 00:31:09.970 align:middle line:90%


00:31:09.970 --> 00:31:16.450 align:middle line:90%
So expansion in graphs--

00:31:16.450 --> 00:31:20.493 align:middle line:90%


00:31:20.493 --> 00:31:20.993 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:20.993 --> 00:31:29.860 align:middle line:84%
So if G is a finite group And
A is a set of generators--

00:31:29.860 --> 00:31:31.520 align:middle line:84%
and i guess that
to have a graph,

00:31:31.520 --> 00:31:35.060 align:middle line:84%
maybe we should say that is a
symmetric set of generators.

00:31:35.060 --> 00:31:36.440 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if
that's important.

00:31:36.440 --> 00:31:37.280 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, let's do it.

00:31:37.280 --> 00:31:40.700 align:middle line:90%


00:31:40.700 --> 00:31:44.780 align:middle line:84%
Then we'll have a Cayley
graph, Cayley graph of G, A--

00:31:44.780 --> 00:31:46.940 align:middle line:90%
so is a graph.

00:31:46.940 --> 00:31:55.100 align:middle line:84%
The vertices are g in
G. And a pair, g1, g2,

00:31:55.100 --> 00:32:05.940 align:middle line:84%
is an edge if and only if g2
is g1 times a or vice versa.

00:32:05.940 --> 00:32:09.260 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so I guess we
should have it symmetric.

00:32:09.260 --> 00:32:14.930 align:middle line:84%
g2 equals g1 times a,
where a is in A. OK.

00:32:14.930 --> 00:32:16.750 align:middle line:84%
And the random walk
we've been imagining

00:32:16.750 --> 00:32:18.870 align:middle line:84%
is basically the random
walk on this graph.

00:32:18.870 --> 00:32:20.830 align:middle line:84%
You start at a vertex,
and you move randomly

00:32:20.830 --> 00:32:22.770 align:middle line:84%
to a neighboring
along the edges.

00:32:22.770 --> 00:32:23.590 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:32:23.590 --> 00:32:25.870 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: How do you identify
SL2 of a finite field

00:32:25.870 --> 00:32:27.100 align:middle line:90%
with a hyperbolic surface?

00:32:27.100 --> 00:32:29.750 align:middle line:90%


00:32:29.750 --> 00:32:32.370 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah, I will--

00:32:32.370 --> 00:32:32.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:32.870 --> 00:32:35.030 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk about the connection
to hyperbolic geometry

00:32:35.030 --> 00:32:37.530 align:middle line:84%
a little later when we talk
about the proof of this theorem.

00:32:37.530 --> 00:32:40.390 align:middle line:90%
Let's do it then.

00:32:40.390 --> 00:32:41.240 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:32:41.240 --> 00:32:41.740 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:41.740 --> 00:32:45.790 align:middle line:90%


00:32:45.790 --> 00:32:47.370 align:middle line:90%
So that's the Cayley graph.

00:32:47.370 --> 00:32:51.270 align:middle line:90%


00:32:51.270 --> 00:32:54.430 align:middle line:84%
And in this graph, if
I have subsets S and T

00:32:54.430 --> 00:32:59.630 align:middle line:84%
inside of the vertices, E of S
and T, the edges from S to T,

00:32:59.630 --> 00:33:07.550 align:middle line:84%
that's going to be the set of
g1, g2 in S cross T so that g1,

00:33:07.550 --> 00:33:10.756 align:middle line:90%
g2 is an edge--

00:33:10.756 --> 00:33:14.120 align:middle line:90%
so the set of edges from S to T.

00:33:14.120 --> 00:33:15.106 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:15.106 --> 00:33:23.540 align:middle line:84%
So proposition-- if we
have C G, A, as above,

00:33:23.540 --> 00:33:26.160 align:middle line:84%
then the number of
edges from S to S

00:33:26.160 --> 00:33:29.840 align:middle line:84%
complement-- so S is going to
be a subset of the vertices.

00:33:29.840 --> 00:33:32.760 align:middle line:84%
The number of these
edges is at least 1

00:33:32.760 --> 00:33:42.520 align:middle line:84%
minus sigma 1 of t A times
A times S times S complement

00:33:42.520 --> 00:33:46.980 align:middle line:90%
over G.

00:33:46.980 --> 00:33:47.480 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:47.480 --> 00:33:51.480 align:middle line:84%
So let's digest
this a little bit.

00:33:51.480 --> 00:33:53.840 align:middle line:84%
So what does this
expression mean?

00:33:53.840 --> 00:33:59.800 align:middle line:84%
Well, this is how many
points there are in the set,

00:33:59.800 --> 00:34:03.422 align:middle line:84%
S. From each of those points,
there are A edges coming out.

00:34:03.422 --> 00:34:04.880 align:middle line:84%
So this is how many
edges there are

00:34:04.880 --> 00:34:09.690 align:middle line:84%
that are leaving points of
S. How many of them do we

00:34:09.690 --> 00:34:11.465 align:middle line:90%
think end up in S complement?

00:34:11.465 --> 00:34:12.590 align:middle line:90%
Well, we don't really know.

00:34:12.590 --> 00:34:16.449 align:middle line:84%
But as a reference point,
if everything was random,

00:34:16.449 --> 00:34:19.090 align:middle line:84%
the fraction of edges that
ended up in S complement

00:34:19.090 --> 00:34:21.969 align:middle line:90%
might be S complement over G.

00:34:21.969 --> 00:34:24.810 align:middle line:84%
So this expression here
would be the typical number

00:34:24.810 --> 00:34:26.969 align:middle line:84%
of edges from S to
S complement if we

00:34:26.969 --> 00:34:32.210 align:middle line:84%
had a random graph where each
vertex was in this many edges.

00:34:32.210 --> 00:34:32.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:32.790 --> 00:34:35.248 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going to say
that the actual number of edges

00:34:35.248 --> 00:34:38.050 align:middle line:84%
is at least some
fraction of that.

00:34:38.050 --> 00:34:42.070 align:middle line:84%
If sigma 1 of TA were 1, this
would be a trivial inequality,

00:34:42.070 --> 00:34:43.090 align:middle line:90%
which is bigger than 0.

00:34:43.090 --> 00:34:46.090 align:middle line:84%
But if sigma 1 is
smaller than 1,

00:34:46.090 --> 00:34:47.909 align:middle line:84%
then this is a
nontrivial inequality.

00:34:47.909 --> 00:34:49.409 align:middle line:84%
And it says that
the number of edges

00:34:49.409 --> 00:34:51.710 align:middle line:84%
is a definite
fraction of what you

00:34:51.710 --> 00:34:52.960 align:middle line:90%
would see in the random model.

00:34:52.960 --> 00:34:55.530 align:middle line:90%


00:34:55.530 --> 00:34:57.370 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:57.370 --> 00:35:00.100 align:middle line:84%
So let's prove this or at
least give a proof sketch.

00:35:00.100 --> 00:35:02.890 align:middle line:90%


00:35:02.890 --> 00:35:07.220 align:middle line:84%
So the key point is that we can
describe this quantity using

00:35:07.220 --> 00:35:08.660 align:middle line:90%
this operator TA.

00:35:08.660 --> 00:35:10.460 align:middle line:84%
And then it becomes
not so surprising

00:35:10.460 --> 00:35:13.700 align:middle line:84%
that the singular value
of TA is relevant.

00:35:13.700 --> 00:35:15.420 align:middle line:90%
How do you do it?

00:35:15.420 --> 00:35:20.980 align:middle line:84%
The number of edges from S to S
complement is the inner product,

00:35:20.980 --> 00:35:26.300 align:middle line:84%
is the inner product of TA of
the characteristic function

00:35:26.300 --> 00:35:30.180 align:middle line:84%
of S with the characteristic
function of S complement.

00:35:30.180 --> 00:35:32.480 align:middle line:84%
And there's a factor
of A in front.

00:35:32.480 --> 00:35:36.100 align:middle line:84%
This is a normalization
if TA had been just--

00:35:36.100 --> 00:35:37.818 align:middle line:90%
TA is an averaging operator.

00:35:37.818 --> 00:35:39.360 align:middle line:84%
But we didn't really
want to average,

00:35:39.360 --> 00:35:40.625 align:middle line:90%
we wanted to count edges.

00:35:40.625 --> 00:35:41.750 align:middle line:90%
So there's an extra factor.

00:35:41.750 --> 00:35:51.300 align:middle line:90%


00:35:51.300 --> 00:35:52.206 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:35:52.206 --> 00:35:54.980 align:middle line:84%
Does this look
plausible to people?

00:35:54.980 --> 00:35:57.660 align:middle line:90%
Should we write this?

00:35:57.660 --> 00:36:00.660 align:middle line:84%
Let's write this
out a little bit.

00:36:00.660 --> 00:36:26.200 align:middle line:84%
So TA 1S of g is 1 over A sum
of a in A of 1S of g a inverse.

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:28.830 align:middle line:90%


00:36:28.830 --> 00:36:31.530 align:middle line:84%
So that's the definition
of the convolution.

00:36:31.530 --> 00:36:40.430 align:middle line:90%


00:36:40.430 --> 00:36:43.030 align:middle line:84%
So then when we take
this inner product,

00:36:43.030 --> 00:36:57.710 align:middle line:84%
we're going to have the sum g in
G 1 over A sum a in A 1S of ga

00:36:57.710 --> 00:37:03.110 align:middle line:90%
inverse 1S complement of g.

00:37:03.110 --> 00:37:09.540 align:middle line:84%
So we'll be counting g's
that are in S complement

00:37:09.540 --> 00:37:14.280 align:middle line:84%
but g a inverses in S. And
that's an edge that starts in S

00:37:14.280 --> 00:37:15.954 align:middle line:90%
and goes to S complement.

00:37:15.954 --> 00:37:18.640 align:middle line:90%


00:37:18.640 --> 00:37:22.520 align:middle line:90%
So S, S complement.

00:37:22.520 --> 00:37:23.840 align:middle line:90%
Over here, we have g.

00:37:23.840 --> 00:37:26.480 align:middle line:90%
Over here, we have g a inverse.

00:37:26.480 --> 00:37:28.308 align:middle line:84%
And those are
connected by an edge.

00:37:28.308 --> 00:37:29.850 align:middle line:84%
That's the thing
that we're counting.

00:37:29.850 --> 00:37:32.720 align:middle line:90%


00:37:32.720 --> 00:37:33.360 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:33.360 --> 00:37:37.298 align:middle line:84%
This double sum here means
going through all the edges.

00:37:37.298 --> 00:37:38.840 align:middle line:84%
But we're only
counting an edge if it

00:37:38.840 --> 00:37:41.280 align:middle line:90%
goes from S to S complement.

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:43.340 align:middle line:84%
And we have this, which
we didn't really want,

00:37:43.340 --> 00:37:46.020 align:middle line:84%
which is why we multiply
by this over here.

00:37:46.020 --> 00:37:52.600 align:middle line:90%


00:37:52.600 --> 00:37:53.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:55.240 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:37:55.240 --> 00:37:56.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:37:56.020 --> 00:38:00.320 align:middle line:84%
So now remember that this
operator sort of splits.

00:38:00.320 --> 00:38:02.790 align:middle line:84%
It takes the constant function
to the constant functions,

00:38:02.790 --> 00:38:05.250 align:middle line:84%
and it takes the mean 0
functions to the mean 0

00:38:05.250 --> 00:38:06.150 align:middle line:90%
functions.

00:38:06.150 --> 00:38:07.930 align:middle line:84%
So we should split
everybody in sight

00:38:07.930 --> 00:38:10.310 align:middle line:84%
into a constant part
and a mean 0 part.

00:38:10.310 --> 00:38:13.090 align:middle line:90%


00:38:13.090 --> 00:38:16.370 align:middle line:90%
So we split.

00:38:16.370 --> 00:38:20.530 align:middle line:84%
1S is S over G-- that's
the constant part--

00:38:20.530 --> 00:38:28.450 align:middle line:84%
plus 1S minus S over G. So
this-- so I'll call it 1S high.

00:38:28.450 --> 00:38:31.770 align:middle line:90%
And it lives in L2 of G0.

00:38:31.770 --> 00:38:32.270 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:32.270 --> 00:38:34.290 align:middle line:84%
Do the same thing
for S complement.

00:38:34.290 --> 00:38:38.650 align:middle line:84%
So now the number of edges
from S to S complement,

00:38:38.650 --> 00:38:43.490 align:middle line:90%
that is A times--

00:38:43.490 --> 00:38:43.990 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:43.990 --> 00:38:46.150 align:middle line:84%
We'll have TA of
the constant parts.

00:38:46.150 --> 00:38:55.650 align:middle line:84%
So that's S, G, S complement G
plus A times the high-frequency

00:38:55.650 --> 00:39:05.100 align:middle line:84%
parts, the mean 0 parts TA of
1S high 1S complement high.

00:39:05.100 --> 00:39:18.600 align:middle line:90%


00:39:18.600 --> 00:39:19.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:19.100 --> 00:39:22.620 align:middle line:90%
So let's call this 0.

00:39:22.620 --> 00:39:24.780 align:middle line:90%
And this is the high part.

00:39:24.780 --> 00:39:31.260 align:middle line:84%
Or let's call this the constant
part, and this is the high part.

00:39:31.260 --> 00:39:33.640 align:middle line:84%
So the rest of it is
just a computation.

00:39:33.640 --> 00:39:35.640 align:middle line:84%
And I won't do the
algebra carefully.

00:39:35.640 --> 00:39:37.180 align:middle line:84%
But if you do the
constant part, you

00:39:37.180 --> 00:39:43.380 align:middle line:84%
get this A S S complement over
G. The constant part exactly

00:39:43.380 --> 00:39:46.700 align:middle line:84%
tracks what would happen if
all the edges were random.

00:39:46.700 --> 00:39:49.197 align:middle line:90%
And then for the high part--

00:39:49.197 --> 00:39:50.780 align:middle line:84%
of course, we won't
compute it exactly

00:39:50.780 --> 00:39:53.420 align:middle line:84%
because we have to know
what the operator TA is.

00:39:53.420 --> 00:40:01.670 align:middle line:84%
But we can bound it by the
norm of TA, the sigma 1 of TA,

00:40:01.670 --> 00:40:12.290 align:middle line:84%
times 1S high in L2 times
1S complement high in L2.

00:40:12.290 --> 00:40:12.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:12.790 --> 00:40:15.230 align:middle line:84%
And then those things are
straightforward to compute,

00:40:15.230 --> 00:40:16.170 align:middle line:90%
those L2 norms.

00:40:16.170 --> 00:40:21.310 align:middle line:84%
And if you compute them,
you get that this is A--

00:40:21.310 --> 00:40:23.430 align:middle line:90%
I'll put the sigma 1 out front.

00:40:23.430 --> 00:40:25.110 align:middle line:90%
And then it's the same thing--

00:40:25.110 --> 00:40:31.710 align:middle line:90%
A S S complement over G. OK.

00:40:31.710 --> 00:40:34.550 align:middle line:84%
So the true answer
is the constant term

00:40:34.550 --> 00:40:36.870 align:middle line:84%
plus the high term, which
is like an error term,

00:40:36.870 --> 00:40:39.310 align:middle line:90%
and whose size is at most this.

00:40:39.310 --> 00:40:42.430 align:middle line:84%
And if sigma 1 is
strictly less than 1,

00:40:42.430 --> 00:40:45.410 align:middle line:84%
then the error term is strictly
smaller than the constant term.

00:40:45.410 --> 00:40:46.870 align:middle line:90%
So something will be left over.

00:40:46.870 --> 00:40:48.130 align:middle line:90%
And that's the inequality.

00:40:48.130 --> 00:40:52.190 align:middle line:90%


00:40:52.190 --> 00:40:52.690 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:52.690 --> 00:40:54.300 align:middle line:90%
So let me make a little remark.

00:40:54.300 --> 00:40:57.360 align:middle line:90%


00:40:57.360 --> 00:41:03.160 align:middle line:84%
If S is smaller than G
over 2, then S complement

00:41:03.160 --> 00:41:04.540 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than G over 2.

00:41:04.540 --> 00:41:06.900 align:middle line:84%
So this is more or less
without loss of generality

00:41:06.900 --> 00:41:09.760 align:middle line:84%
if you switch the roles
of S and S complement.

00:41:09.760 --> 00:41:11.640 align:middle line:84%
But it means S
complement is at least G

00:41:11.640 --> 00:41:15.760 align:middle line:84%
over 2, which means that this
whole fraction has order of 1.

00:41:15.760 --> 00:41:20.800 align:middle line:84%
So then we get that the number
of edges from S to S complement

00:41:20.800 --> 00:41:28.640 align:middle line:84%
is at least 1/2 sigma
1 of TA A times S.

00:41:28.640 --> 00:41:31.880 align:middle line:84%
So it's at least a
definite fraction

00:41:31.880 --> 00:41:36.960 align:middle line:84%
of all of the possible edges
that it could be leaving us.

00:41:36.960 --> 00:41:37.460 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:37.460 --> 00:41:41.130 align:middle line:84%
So this property here is
called being an expander graph.

00:41:41.130 --> 00:41:43.880 align:middle line:90%


00:41:43.880 --> 00:41:48.400 align:middle line:84%
Because if you take a set that's
less than half of the graph

00:41:48.400 --> 00:41:51.960 align:middle line:84%
and then you add to it all of
the edges that are leaving it,

00:41:51.960 --> 00:41:53.860 align:middle line:84%
then it will get
significantly bigger.

00:41:53.860 --> 00:41:54.820 align:middle line:90%
It will expand.

00:41:54.820 --> 00:41:56.470 align:middle line:84%
So it's called an
expander graph.

00:41:56.470 --> 00:42:00.130 align:middle line:90%


00:42:00.130 --> 00:42:00.630 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:42:00.630 --> 00:42:02.650 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:42:02.650 --> 00:42:10.650 align:middle line:84%
So this proposition shows that
if this sigma 1 is strictly less

00:42:10.650 --> 00:42:13.530 align:middle line:84%
than 1-- it's something
like in Selberg's theorem--

00:42:13.530 --> 00:42:16.130 align:middle line:84%
then the edges in the
graph behave in this way,

00:42:16.130 --> 00:42:19.490 align:middle line:90%
that it's an expander graph.

00:42:19.490 --> 00:42:20.390 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:42:20.390 --> 00:42:23.180 align:middle line:90%


00:42:23.180 --> 00:42:24.410 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:42:24.410 --> 00:42:26.590 align:middle line:84%
So Selberg did not state
his theorem in this way.

00:42:26.590 --> 00:42:28.330 align:middle line:90%
So this is slightly ahistorical.

00:42:28.330 --> 00:42:30.410 align:middle line:84%
But Selberg's
theorem plus things

00:42:30.410 --> 00:42:33.090 align:middle line:84%
that are not very
difficult in hindsight

00:42:33.090 --> 00:42:38.090 align:middle line:84%
show that this Cayley graph of
SL2 Fp is an expander graph.

00:42:38.090 --> 00:42:40.093 align:middle line:90%
And it is in a sense the first--

00:42:40.093 --> 00:42:42.010 align:middle line:84%
Selberg didn't quite say
this, but in a sense,

00:42:42.010 --> 00:42:46.930 align:middle line:84%
this was the first proof that
any graph was an expander graph.

00:42:46.930 --> 00:42:51.710 align:middle line:84%
Expander graphs were officially
defined in 1970 by Pinsker

00:42:51.710 --> 00:42:54.170 align:middle line:84%
and something pretty close
by Kolmogorov and Barzdin

00:42:54.170 --> 00:42:55.280 align:middle line:90%
in the '60s.

00:42:55.280 --> 00:42:58.860 align:middle line:84%
And all of those people
realized that random graphs

00:42:58.860 --> 00:42:59.990 align:middle line:90%
were expander graphs.

00:42:59.990 --> 00:43:04.800 align:middle line:90%


00:43:04.800 --> 00:43:05.300 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:43:05.300 --> 00:43:07.420 align:middle line:84%
So maybe many people have
seen, but it's really

00:43:07.420 --> 00:43:08.660 align:middle line:90%
a remarkable thing.

00:43:08.660 --> 00:43:11.660 align:middle line:84%
So just for comparison,
like a simple graph that we

00:43:11.660 --> 00:43:15.220 align:middle line:84%
might think of that we
can easily visualize

00:43:15.220 --> 00:43:18.180 align:middle line:90%
would be an n-by-n grid.

00:43:18.180 --> 00:43:20.760 align:middle line:84%
And that kind of graph is
not an expander at all.

00:43:20.760 --> 00:43:23.780 align:middle line:84%
So an n-by-n grid has
n squared vertices.

00:43:23.780 --> 00:43:26.460 align:middle line:84%
But you can cut it in
half with a vertical line,

00:43:26.460 --> 00:43:29.260 align:middle line:90%
and you only cut n edges.

00:43:29.260 --> 00:43:30.620 align:middle line:90%
So the number of edges--

00:43:30.620 --> 00:43:33.080 align:middle line:84%
so S and S complement are
each about half of the graph.

00:43:33.080 --> 00:43:37.460 align:middle line:84%
The number of edges between
them is much smaller than S.

00:43:37.460 --> 00:43:39.080 align:middle line:90%
So these are very large graphs.

00:43:39.080 --> 00:43:41.220 align:middle line:84%
But the number of edges
it takes to cut it in half

00:43:41.220 --> 00:43:43.580 align:middle line:84%
is comparable to
all of the edges.

00:43:43.580 --> 00:43:48.020 align:middle line:90%
And most graphs are like that.

00:43:48.020 --> 00:43:49.700 align:middle line:84%
But before people
realized it, it

00:43:49.700 --> 00:43:51.460 align:middle line:84%
was surprising and
counterintuitive

00:43:51.460 --> 00:43:53.310 align:middle line:90%
that any graphs were like that.

00:43:53.310 --> 00:43:56.390 align:middle line:84%
And it's a very significant
fact in many domains

00:43:56.390 --> 00:43:57.380 align:middle line:90%
of math and science.

00:43:57.380 --> 00:44:03.870 align:middle line:90%


00:44:03.870 --> 00:44:04.370 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:04.370 --> 00:44:05.430 align:middle line:90%
Let me pause there.

00:44:05.430 --> 00:44:08.950 align:middle line:84%
And questions about
Selberg's theorem

00:44:08.950 --> 00:44:11.750 align:middle line:84%
and this setup, mixing
and expansion and--

00:44:11.750 --> 00:44:19.277 align:middle line:90%


00:44:19.277 --> 00:44:21.110 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So the point
of A being generators

00:44:21.110 --> 00:44:23.990 align:middle line:90%
is just so that it's connected?

00:44:23.990 --> 00:44:26.030 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH:
Yes, that's right.

00:44:26.030 --> 00:44:32.250 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, what is the
point of A being generators?

00:44:32.250 --> 00:44:38.590 align:middle line:90%


00:44:38.590 --> 00:44:42.270 align:middle line:84%
So if A did not
generate the group,

00:44:42.270 --> 00:44:44.510 align:middle line:84%
then this graph would
be disconnected,

00:44:44.510 --> 00:44:47.670 align:middle line:90%
and then it wouldn't mix at all.

00:44:47.670 --> 00:44:51.000 align:middle line:90%
So make a remark--

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:56.600 align:middle line:84%
suppose that A is in a
finite group and that H--

00:44:56.600 --> 00:45:02.560 align:middle line:84%
so the subgroup
generated by A is

00:45:02.560 --> 00:45:05.070 align:middle line:90%
H, which is a proper subgroup.

00:45:05.070 --> 00:45:09.570 align:middle line:90%


00:45:09.570 --> 00:45:10.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:10.070 --> 00:45:15.000 align:middle line:84%
So then if we take
TA and we apply it

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:17.720 align:middle line:84%
to the characteristic
function of this subgroup,

00:45:17.720 --> 00:45:19.780 align:middle line:84%
since all of these guys
are in the subgroup,

00:45:19.780 --> 00:45:21.900 align:middle line:84%
we would just stay
in the subgroup.

00:45:21.900 --> 00:45:23.000 align:middle line:90%
So this would be 1H.

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:26.120 align:middle line:90%


00:45:26.120 --> 00:45:26.620 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:26.620 --> 00:45:32.200 align:middle line:84%
And that implies, with a teeny
bit of work, that sigma 1 of TA

00:45:32.200 --> 00:45:33.060 align:middle line:90%
would be 1.

00:45:33.060 --> 00:45:35.260 align:middle line:90%


00:45:35.260 --> 00:45:35.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:35.760 --> 00:45:37.427 align:middle line:84%
One thing we could
see is that no matter

00:45:37.427 --> 00:45:39.100 align:middle line:84%
how many times we
repeat this operation,

00:45:39.100 --> 00:45:41.320 align:middle line:84%
we will never mix
over the whole group

00:45:41.320 --> 00:45:42.840 align:middle line:84%
because we'll
never get out of H.

00:45:42.840 --> 00:45:47.840 align:middle line:84%
And so based on what we've
seen before, this should be 1.

00:45:47.840 --> 00:45:49.000 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:50.670 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Does it make A big--

00:45:50.670 --> 00:45:57.057 align:middle line:84%
does it just make the graph
more likely to be expander?

00:45:57.057 --> 00:45:57.890 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:45:57.890 --> 00:45:59.432 align:middle line:84%
So the question is,
if we make A big,

00:45:59.432 --> 00:46:04.130 align:middle line:84%
is the graph more likely
to be an expander?

00:46:04.130 --> 00:46:05.210 align:middle line:90%
Perhaps.

00:46:05.210 --> 00:46:09.130 align:middle line:84%
So we could take A big,
and then it would--

00:46:09.130 --> 00:46:11.010 align:middle line:90%
so we're allowed to take A big.

00:46:11.010 --> 00:46:15.230 align:middle line:84%
And we will talk in a little
bit about what we can say.

00:46:15.230 --> 00:46:17.250 align:middle line:84%
If we just know that A
is big, what does that

00:46:17.250 --> 00:46:19.490 align:middle line:90%
tell us about sigma of TA?

00:46:19.490 --> 00:46:21.930 align:middle line:90%
We'll talk about that.

00:46:21.930 --> 00:46:23.850 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:46:23.850 --> 00:46:26.370 align:middle line:84%
So another remark
I wanted to make

00:46:26.370 --> 00:46:30.170 align:middle line:84%
is that the first proof of this
theorem was very difficult.

00:46:30.170 --> 00:46:33.410 align:middle line:84%
So the first proof
depended on-- so it

00:46:33.410 --> 00:46:36.550 align:middle line:84%
had some interesting analysis
related to hyperbolic geometry.

00:46:36.550 --> 00:46:38.650 align:middle line:84%
But then it depended on
the Riemann hypothesis

00:46:38.650 --> 00:46:40.120 align:middle line:90%
for curves over finite fields.

00:46:40.120 --> 00:46:43.970 align:middle line:90%


00:46:43.970 --> 00:46:46.692 align:middle line:84%
So that's a beautiful
and important theorem.

00:46:46.692 --> 00:46:48.900 align:middle line:84%
But if you wanted to include
the whole proof of that,

00:46:48.900 --> 00:46:50.775 align:middle line:84%
then the proof of this
theorem is effectively

00:46:50.775 --> 00:46:54.780 align:middle line:84%
several hundred pages long and
has a lot of algebraic geometry.

00:46:54.780 --> 00:47:00.380 align:middle line:84%
And in around the early 1990s,
Sarnak and Xue gave a much

00:47:00.380 --> 00:47:07.130 align:middle line:84%
simpler proof, which is the
proof that we'll talk about.

00:47:07.130 --> 00:47:18.180 align:middle line:90%


00:47:18.180 --> 00:47:18.680 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:18.680 --> 00:47:20.138 align:middle line:84%
So in the rest of
the class, I will

00:47:20.138 --> 00:47:25.420 align:middle line:84%
start to describe the
proof by Sarnak and Xue

00:47:25.420 --> 00:47:29.130 align:middle line:84%
and introduce the
first key idea.

00:47:29.130 --> 00:47:32.820 align:middle line:90%


00:47:32.820 --> 00:47:33.400 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:47:33.400 --> 00:47:38.422 align:middle line:90%


00:47:38.422 --> 00:47:38.922 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:38.922 --> 00:47:41.694 align:middle line:90%


00:47:41.694 --> 00:47:47.750 align:middle line:84%
So the first idea, this idea has
to do with the representation

00:47:47.750 --> 00:47:52.440 align:middle line:90%
theory of the group SL2 Fp.

00:47:52.440 --> 00:47:54.950 align:middle line:90%


00:47:54.950 --> 00:47:59.390 align:middle line:90%
So proposition-- OK.

00:47:59.390 --> 00:48:04.070 align:middle line:84%
So if we have a representation--
so a representation is a group

00:48:04.070 --> 00:48:08.090 align:middle line:84%
homomorphism to-- it's a
unitary representation--

00:48:08.090 --> 00:48:12.830 align:middle line:84%
so to the unitary
group in d dimensions.

00:48:12.830 --> 00:48:18.730 align:middle line:84%
So this is a representation,
meaning a group homomorphism.

00:48:18.730 --> 00:48:25.030 align:middle line:90%


00:48:25.030 --> 00:48:25.530 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:25.530 --> 00:48:28.095 align:middle line:84%
And so there's the trivial
representation, where everything

00:48:28.095 --> 00:48:28.970 align:middle line:90%
goes to the identity.

00:48:28.970 --> 00:48:32.350 align:middle line:84%
But let me say it is a
nontrivial representation.

00:48:32.350 --> 00:48:35.630 align:middle line:84%
Then actually, d
needs to be quite big.

00:48:35.630 --> 00:48:38.530 align:middle line:90%
d is at least p plus 1 over 2.

00:48:38.530 --> 00:48:47.040 align:middle line:90%


00:48:47.040 --> 00:48:48.937 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:48.937 --> 00:48:50.520 align:middle line:84%
So before we prove
this theorem, let's

00:48:50.520 --> 00:48:52.560 align:middle line:84%
try to put it in context
by trying to think

00:48:52.560 --> 00:48:55.680 align:middle line:90%
about group representations.

00:48:55.680 --> 00:48:58.640 align:middle line:84%
Where would we find a
group representation?

00:48:58.640 --> 00:48:59.160 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:59.160 --> 00:49:02.280 align:middle line:90%
Well, SL2 Fp acts on itself.

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:08.200 align:middle line:84%
So it acts on the space that
we started with L2 of G.

00:49:08.200 --> 00:49:14.640 align:middle line:84%
So any group G acts on
L2 of G by the action

00:49:14.640 --> 00:49:15.780 align:middle line:90%
that we wrote down.

00:49:15.780 --> 00:49:19.420 align:middle line:84%
You take a function, and you
shift the space under it.

00:49:19.420 --> 00:49:19.920 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:19.920 --> 00:49:21.860 align:middle line:90%
That action is not trivial.

00:49:21.860 --> 00:49:24.300 align:middle line:84%
Only the constant
functions are fixed.

00:49:24.300 --> 00:49:25.880 align:middle line:90%
So that's a nontrivial action.

00:49:25.880 --> 00:49:29.360 align:middle line:84%
And the dimension of this
space is the cardinality of G.

00:49:29.360 --> 00:49:33.560 align:middle line:84%
So for this group, that
would be about p cubed.

00:49:33.560 --> 00:49:40.280 align:middle line:84%
So cardinality of
SL2 Fp sub f p cubed.

00:49:40.280 --> 00:49:40.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:40.780 --> 00:49:43.480 align:middle line:90%


00:49:43.480 --> 00:49:44.280 align:middle line:90%
What else?

00:49:44.280 --> 00:49:47.660 align:middle line:84%
Well, if you have
a subgroup of G--

00:49:47.660 --> 00:49:51.940 align:middle line:90%
H is a subgroup of G--

00:49:51.940 --> 00:50:01.280 align:middle line:84%
then G acts on G mod H. And
so it acts on this as a set.

00:50:01.280 --> 00:50:07.060 align:middle line:84%
And so it acts on L2 of G mod
H by a unitary representation.

00:50:07.060 --> 00:50:13.340 align:middle line:84%
And so the dimension
of L2 of G mod H

00:50:13.340 --> 00:50:16.100 align:middle line:84%
is the cardinality
of G mod H, which

00:50:16.100 --> 00:50:21.540 align:middle line:84%
is the cardinality of G divided
by the cardinality of H. OK.

00:50:21.540 --> 00:50:24.680 align:middle line:84%
So let's think of some
subgroups of SL2 Fp.

00:50:24.680 --> 00:50:33.100 align:middle line:90%


00:50:33.100 --> 00:50:36.010 align:middle line:84%
I think of-- the diagonal
subgroup looks like this.

00:50:36.010 --> 00:50:39.040 align:middle line:90%


00:50:39.040 --> 00:50:42.870 align:middle line:84%
And the size of the diagonal
subgroup is around p.

00:50:42.870 --> 00:50:47.810 align:middle line:84%
There's the unipotent
subgroup, looks like this.

00:50:47.810 --> 00:50:51.030 align:middle line:84%
Size of the unipotent
subgroup is p.

00:50:51.030 --> 00:50:53.090 align:middle line:84%
And you could mix
these together.

00:50:53.090 --> 00:50:55.715 align:middle line:84%
So there's the upper
triangular subgroup.

00:50:55.715 --> 00:50:57.090 align:middle line:84%
But we already
used the letter u.

00:50:57.090 --> 00:51:00.390 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to call
this B for Borel.

00:51:00.390 --> 00:51:04.910 align:middle line:90%
So I'll write it a a inverse t.

00:51:04.910 --> 00:51:05.950 align:middle line:90%
That's a subgroup.

00:51:05.950 --> 00:51:08.110 align:middle line:84%
And the size of the
upper triangular subgroup

00:51:08.110 --> 00:51:10.190 align:middle line:90%
is around p squared.

00:51:10.190 --> 00:51:13.230 align:middle line:84%
So that's the biggest one that
we have come up with here.

00:51:13.230 --> 00:51:16.930 align:middle line:90%
And if you plug this in here--

00:51:16.930 --> 00:51:24.310 align:middle line:84%
so if you take SL2 Fp
modulo rho, that's around p.

00:51:24.310 --> 00:51:27.690 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the right
order of magnitude.

00:51:27.690 --> 00:51:32.236 align:middle line:90%


00:51:32.236 --> 00:51:32.736 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:32.736 --> 00:51:35.450 align:middle line:84%
And this is an interesting
fact about this group,

00:51:35.450 --> 00:51:37.870 align:middle line:84%
which is extremely different
from abelian groups.

00:51:37.870 --> 00:51:42.920 align:middle line:84%
So for an abelian group, every
irreducible representation

00:51:42.920 --> 00:51:43.980 align:middle line:90%
is one-dimensional.

00:51:43.980 --> 00:51:47.080 align:middle line:84%
So there are lots and lots of
representations where d is 1.

00:51:47.080 --> 00:51:48.360 align:middle line:90%
But for SL2 Fp.

00:51:48.360 --> 00:51:49.500 align:middle line:90%
Life is very different.

00:51:49.500 --> 00:51:52.960 align:middle line:84%
All of them have
very large dimension.

00:51:52.960 --> 00:51:55.564 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:55.564 --> 00:51:57.070 align:middle line:90%
So let's prove this theorem.

00:51:57.070 --> 00:52:01.160 align:middle line:90%


00:52:01.160 --> 00:52:03.800 align:middle line:84%
So I had heard about
this theorem years ago.

00:52:03.800 --> 00:52:06.000 align:middle line:84%
And I always assumed that
to prove this theorem,

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:08.500 align:middle line:84%
one had to study a lot
of representation theory.

00:52:08.500 --> 00:52:10.450 align:middle line:84%
And I was a little
intimidated by it.

00:52:10.450 --> 00:52:12.200 align:middle line:84%
But then I read the
proof as I was getting

00:52:12.200 --> 00:52:13.300 align:middle line:90%
ready to teach this class.

00:52:13.300 --> 00:52:15.800 align:middle line:84%
And actually, it
doesn't require anything

00:52:15.800 --> 00:52:19.960 align:middle line:84%
that's outside of a good
undergraduate algebra

00:52:19.960 --> 00:52:21.592 align:middle line:90%
curriculum.

00:52:21.592 --> 00:52:22.550 align:middle line:90%
And it's quite elegant.

00:52:22.550 --> 00:52:28.400 align:middle line:90%


00:52:28.400 --> 00:52:29.520 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:52:29.520 --> 00:52:30.570 align:middle line:90%
So here's the proof.

00:52:30.570 --> 00:52:33.680 align:middle line:90%


00:52:33.680 --> 00:52:38.400 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to focus on
this matrix for a little while

00:52:38.400 --> 00:52:40.810 align:middle line:84%
and try to figure out what
the representation does

00:52:40.810 --> 00:52:43.250 align:middle line:90%
with this matrix.

00:52:43.250 --> 00:52:48.770 align:middle line:84%
So let's suppose for now
that rho of this matrix

00:52:48.770 --> 00:52:50.510 align:middle line:90%
is not just the identity.

00:52:50.510 --> 00:52:55.730 align:middle line:90%


00:52:55.730 --> 00:52:59.650 align:middle line:84%
Actually, let me say it
in a different order.

00:52:59.650 --> 00:53:04.370 align:middle line:84%
So u is that matrix and
v is this matrix, which

00:53:04.370 --> 00:53:06.730 align:middle line:90%
is very similar to u.

00:53:06.730 --> 00:53:09.510 align:middle line:90%
And we'll make the remark that--

00:53:09.510 --> 00:53:12.690 align:middle line:84%
so exercise-- at this point,
I won't include the details.

00:53:12.690 --> 00:53:17.230 align:middle line:90%
u and v generate SL2 of Fp.

00:53:17.230 --> 00:53:20.470 align:middle line:90%


00:53:20.470 --> 00:53:20.970 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:53:20.970 --> 00:53:24.170 align:middle line:84%
If you play around a little
bit, you can see this.

00:53:24.170 --> 00:53:24.670 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:53:24.670 --> 00:53:26.930 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, if we have a
nontrivial representation,

00:53:26.930 --> 00:53:30.050 align:middle line:84%
these cannot both
go to the identity.

00:53:30.050 --> 00:53:33.690 align:middle line:90%
So rho is nontrivial.

00:53:33.690 --> 00:53:38.780 align:middle line:84%
So either rho of u or row
of v is not the identity.

00:53:38.780 --> 00:53:40.800 align:middle line:84%
And u and v are so
similar to each other,

00:53:40.800 --> 00:53:42.400 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't really
matter which one.

00:53:42.400 --> 00:53:46.000 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to say, essentially
without loss of generality,

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:51.060 align:middle line:90%
rho of u is not i lamda

00:53:51.060 --> 00:53:51.560 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:53:51.560 --> 00:53:53.360 align:middle line:90%
Now let's think about rho of u.

00:53:53.360 --> 00:54:03.840 align:middle line:90%


00:54:03.840 --> 00:54:08.140 align:middle line:84%
There's something quite special
about this matrix, which

00:54:08.140 --> 00:54:18.700 align:middle line:84%
is that it is conjugate
to powers of itself.

00:54:18.700 --> 00:54:20.540 align:middle line:90%
Let me write that down.

00:54:20.540 --> 00:54:25.740 align:middle line:84%
So suppose take a diagonal
matrix, a, a inverse.

00:54:25.740 --> 00:54:29.180 align:middle line:84%
And I put this
matrix in the middle.

00:54:29.180 --> 00:54:30.640 align:middle line:90%
And then I want to conjugate it.

00:54:30.640 --> 00:54:33.020 align:middle line:84%
So now I put on the
other side the inverse.

00:54:33.020 --> 00:54:38.870 align:middle line:84%
So this is the conjugate
of my matrix u.

00:54:38.870 --> 00:54:40.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:54:40.870 --> 00:54:45.270 align:middle line:90%
So I multiply this by this.

00:54:45.270 --> 00:54:50.670 align:middle line:84%
I multiply the top row by a and
the bottom row by a inverse.

00:54:50.670 --> 00:54:55.310 align:middle line:90%
So I get a a 0 a inverse.

00:54:55.310 --> 00:54:56.770 align:middle line:90%
And then I still have this guy.

00:54:56.770 --> 00:55:00.510 align:middle line:90%


00:55:00.510 --> 00:55:03.310 align:middle line:84%
Now, when I multiply
these matrices together,

00:55:03.310 --> 00:55:07.510 align:middle line:84%
I multiply the left column by
a inverse and the right column

00:55:07.510 --> 00:55:09.350 align:middle line:90%
by a.

00:55:09.350 --> 00:55:11.510 align:middle line:90%
The diagonals cancel.

00:55:11.510 --> 00:55:14.960 align:middle line:90%
But I get 1 0 1 a squared.

00:55:14.960 --> 00:55:22.910 align:middle line:90%


00:55:22.910 --> 00:55:38.440 align:middle line:84%
OK, so see that u is conjugate
tp u to the power a squared.

00:55:38.440 --> 00:55:42.110 align:middle line:84%
And this is for
any a in F we saw.

00:55:42.110 --> 00:55:52.520 align:middle line:90%


00:55:52.520 --> 00:55:54.720 align:middle line:84%
So that is a special
and really interesting

00:55:54.720 --> 00:56:00.040 align:middle line:84%
feature of this
element of my group.

00:56:00.040 --> 00:56:02.720 align:middle line:84%
And so now I have
a representation.

00:56:02.720 --> 00:56:11.320 align:middle line:84%
And rho of u is conjugate to
rho of u of a squared, which

00:56:11.320 --> 00:56:14.880 align:middle line:90%
is rho of u to the a squared.

00:56:14.880 --> 00:56:16.080 align:middle line:90%
So now I have a matrix.

00:56:16.080 --> 00:56:17.420 align:middle line:90%
I have a unitary matrix.

00:56:17.420 --> 00:56:21.900 align:middle line:84%
And it is conjugate to
a big power of itself.

00:56:21.900 --> 00:56:22.400 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:22.400 --> 00:56:24.880 align:middle line:84%
In the world of
matrices, it's not

00:56:24.880 --> 00:56:27.280 align:middle line:90%
so easy to get that to happen.

00:56:27.280 --> 00:56:31.040 align:middle line:84%
So this group has an
interesting property

00:56:31.040 --> 00:56:35.130 align:middle line:84%
that has an element which is
conjugate to many different

00:56:35.130 --> 00:56:37.450 align:middle line:90%
powers of itself.

00:56:37.450 --> 00:56:40.570 align:middle line:84%
And in matrices, it's
not so easy to find

00:56:40.570 --> 00:56:45.050 align:middle line:84%
a matrix which is conjugate to
many different powers of itself.

00:56:45.050 --> 00:56:46.050 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:56:46.050 --> 00:56:51.080 align:middle line:84%
Because of how the
eigenvalues behave.

00:56:51.080 --> 00:56:54.370 align:middle line:90%


00:56:54.370 --> 00:56:55.250 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:55.250 --> 00:56:57.230 align:middle line:84%
So now let's think
about eigenvalues.

00:56:57.230 --> 00:57:36.180 align:middle line:90%


00:57:36.180 --> 00:57:37.740 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:37.740 --> 00:57:42.970 align:middle line:84%
So rho of u is in
U of d is a matrix.

00:57:42.970 --> 00:57:47.780 align:middle line:90%


00:57:47.780 --> 00:57:57.540 align:middle line:84%
And if rho of u is conjugate
to rho of u to the a squared,

00:57:57.540 --> 00:58:02.180 align:middle line:84%
then that tells us that the
eigenvalues, the spectrum of rho

00:58:02.180 --> 00:58:08.060 align:middle line:84%
of u is the same as the
eigenvalues of rho of u

00:58:08.060 --> 00:58:08.990 align:middle line:90%
to the a squared.

00:58:08.990 --> 00:58:11.500 align:middle line:90%


00:58:11.500 --> 00:58:15.100 align:middle line:84%
Two conjugate matrices
have the same eigenvalues.

00:58:15.100 --> 00:58:18.940 align:middle line:84%
But if you take a matrix
and raise it to a power,

00:58:18.940 --> 00:58:21.580 align:middle line:84%
the eigenvalues are
all raised to a power.

00:58:21.580 --> 00:58:27.290 align:middle line:84%
So this is the eigenvalues
of rho of u to the a squared.

00:58:27.290 --> 00:58:34.230 align:middle line:90%


00:58:34.230 --> 00:58:34.730 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:34.730 --> 00:58:36.990 align:middle line:84%
So for instance, you
could take a to be 2.

00:58:36.990 --> 00:58:40.910 align:middle line:84%
And it tells if you have
an eigenvalue of rho of u,

00:58:40.910 --> 00:58:42.950 align:middle line:84%
you raise it to the fourth
power, that will also

00:58:42.950 --> 00:58:44.690 align:middle line:90%
be an eigenvalue of rho of u.

00:58:44.690 --> 00:58:46.830 align:middle line:90%
And you can keep doing that.

00:58:46.830 --> 00:58:47.790 align:middle line:90%
And it's not just 4.

00:58:47.790 --> 00:58:49.280 align:middle line:84%
We have many choices
for a squared.

00:58:49.280 --> 00:58:52.750 align:middle line:90%


00:58:52.750 --> 00:58:53.950 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:53.950 --> 00:58:56.630 align:middle line:84%
So let's think about what
the eigenvalues of rho of u

00:58:56.630 --> 00:58:58.310 align:middle line:90%
may be like--

00:58:58.310 --> 00:59:04.750 align:middle line:90%
so eigenvalues of rho of u.

00:59:04.750 --> 00:59:06.970 align:middle line:84%
So this is an amazing
fact about them.

00:59:06.970 --> 00:59:08.390 align:middle line:84%
And there's a more
pedestrian fact

00:59:08.390 --> 00:59:09.950 align:middle line:90%
that we should also observe.

00:59:09.950 --> 00:59:14.150 align:middle line:84%
We know that u to the
p is the identity.

00:59:14.150 --> 00:59:18.950 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, rho of u
to the p is the identity.

00:59:18.950 --> 00:59:24.110 align:middle line:84%
So then if lambda is an
eigenvalue of rho of u,

00:59:24.110 --> 00:59:27.690 align:middle line:84%
then we get that
lambda to the p is 1.

00:59:27.690 --> 00:59:28.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:28.190 --> 00:59:31.330 align:middle line:84%
So the eigenvalues of rho of u,
they're all p-th roots of unity.

00:59:31.330 --> 00:59:38.040 align:middle line:90%


00:59:38.040 --> 00:59:39.380 align:middle line:90%
So we get the following.

00:59:39.380 --> 00:59:45.880 align:middle line:84%
If lambda is an eigenvalue of
rho of u, then lambda to the p

00:59:45.880 --> 00:59:50.280 align:middle line:84%
is 1 and lambda to
the a squared is also

00:59:50.280 --> 00:59:52.980 align:middle line:90%
an eigenvalue of rho of u.

00:59:52.980 --> 01:00:01.120 align:middle line:90%


01:00:01.120 --> 01:00:02.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:02.640 --> 01:00:07.640 align:middle line:84%
So since lambda
to the p is 1, we

01:00:07.640 --> 01:00:09.800 align:middle line:90%
only care about a squared mod p.

01:00:09.800 --> 01:00:14.080 align:middle line:90%
So we could put mod p there.

01:00:14.080 --> 01:00:25.720 align:middle line:84%
And there are p minus 1 over
2 quadratic residues mod p.

01:00:25.720 --> 01:00:28.610 align:middle line:84%
So this a squared mod p, it
could be any quadratic residue

01:00:28.610 --> 01:00:29.190 align:middle line:90%
mod p.

01:00:29.190 --> 01:00:31.570 align:middle line:84%
There are p minus
1 over 2 of them.

01:00:31.570 --> 01:00:33.290 align:middle line:84%
And if you take a
p-th root of unity

01:00:33.290 --> 01:00:36.450 align:middle line:84%
and you raise it to a power
that's between 1 and p,

01:00:36.450 --> 01:00:38.010 align:middle line:90%
you'll change it.

01:00:38.010 --> 01:00:39.930 align:middle line:90%
So lambda is a primitive.

01:00:39.930 --> 01:00:44.090 align:middle line:84%
So if lambda is
not 1, then lambda

01:00:44.090 --> 01:00:46.100 align:middle line:84%
is a primitive
p-th root of unity.

01:00:46.100 --> 01:00:50.090 align:middle line:90%


01:00:50.090 --> 01:00:54.330 align:middle line:84%
And that tells us that the
lambda to the a squared mod p

01:00:54.330 --> 01:01:02.870 align:middle line:84%
are all distinct for the p minus
1 over 2 quadratic residues.

01:01:02.870 --> 01:01:03.370 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:03.370 --> 01:01:06.490 align:middle line:84%
So we now have
seen that there are

01:01:06.490 --> 01:01:08.970 align:middle line:84%
an awful lot of different
eigenvalues, which

01:01:08.970 --> 01:01:12.890 align:middle line:84%
can only happen if the matrix
is in a large dimension.

01:01:12.890 --> 01:01:17.390 align:middle line:84%
So that gives us that d is
at least p plus 1 over 2.

01:01:17.390 --> 01:01:20.930 align:middle line:90%


01:01:20.930 --> 01:01:22.530 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:22.530 --> 01:01:24.690 align:middle line:84%
So how do we know
that rho of you

01:01:24.690 --> 01:01:27.860 align:middle line:90%
has an eigenvalue that's not 1?

01:01:27.860 --> 01:01:31.860 align:middle line:84%
Well, if all the eigenvalues
were 1, then rho of u

01:01:31.860 --> 01:01:34.340 align:middle line:84%
is conjugate to a matrix
with 1's on the diagonals

01:01:34.340 --> 01:01:36.445 align:middle line:90%
and some upper triangular stuff.

01:01:36.445 --> 01:01:37.820 align:middle line:84%
And if you raise
that to a power,

01:01:37.820 --> 01:01:40.940 align:middle line:90%
you'll never get the identity.

01:01:40.940 --> 01:01:42.560 align:middle line:90%
There's an exercise.

01:01:42.560 --> 01:01:44.860 align:middle line:84%
So there's a little
something more to

01:01:44.860 --> 01:01:51.860 align:middle line:84%
exercise-- if the
eigenvalues of rho of u

01:01:51.860 --> 01:01:59.660 align:middle line:84%
are exactly the set 1 and
rho of u to the p equals 1,

01:01:59.660 --> 01:02:03.300 align:middle line:90%
then rho of u is the identity.

01:02:03.300 --> 01:02:06.760 align:middle line:90%
I'll leave the matrix details.

01:02:06.760 --> 01:02:07.260 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:02:07.260 --> 01:02:14.420 align:middle line:90%


01:02:14.420 --> 01:02:16.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:16.100 --> 01:02:20.620 align:middle line:84%
So all the representations
of SL2 are really big.

01:02:20.620 --> 01:02:23.100 align:middle line:90%
Why does that matter?

01:02:23.100 --> 01:02:24.770 align:middle line:90%
Let's do another proposition.

01:02:24.770 --> 01:02:39.350 align:middle line:90%


01:02:39.350 --> 01:02:46.930 align:middle line:84%
So proposition 2-- you
take sigma 1 of T mu.

01:02:46.930 --> 01:02:52.250 align:middle line:84%
So mu is a probability
measure on SL2 Fp.

01:02:52.250 --> 01:02:56.830 align:middle line:90%


01:02:56.830 --> 01:03:01.030 align:middle line:84%
Then sigma 1 of this guy, if
you square it and you multiply

01:03:01.030 --> 01:03:10.150 align:middle line:84%
by d plus 1 over 2, that is at
most the size of SL2 Fp times mu

01:03:10.150 --> 01:03:13.350 align:middle line:90%
L2 squared.

01:03:13.350 --> 01:03:18.830 align:middle line:84%
Simplifying the algebra a little
bit, sigma 1 of T mu squared

01:03:18.830 --> 01:03:23.430 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than around 1 over
p squared times mu L2 squared.

01:03:23.430 --> 01:03:29.500 align:middle line:90%


01:03:29.500 --> 01:03:30.000 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:34.160 align:middle line:90%


01:03:34.160 --> 01:03:35.003 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:03:35.003 --> 01:03:37.420 align:middle line:84%
So we come back to the question
from earlier in the class.

01:03:37.420 --> 01:03:41.000 align:middle line:84%
How are singular values
related to eigenvalues?

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:52.920 align:middle line:84%
So sigma i of T mu squared is
lambda i of T mu T mu star,

01:03:52.920 --> 01:03:57.520 align:middle line:90%
i-th eigenvalue of this matrix.

01:03:57.520 --> 01:04:02.440 align:middle line:84%
And the key observation is that
the eigenspaces of this matrix

01:04:02.440 --> 01:04:04.560 align:middle line:90%
have a G action on them.

01:04:04.560 --> 01:04:06.960 align:middle line:84%
And except for the
constant functions,

01:04:06.960 --> 01:04:10.280 align:middle line:90%
the eigenspaces are not trivial.

01:04:10.280 --> 01:04:11.140 align:middle line:90%
There's the key.

01:04:11.140 --> 01:04:14.040 align:middle line:90%


01:04:14.040 --> 01:04:23.730 align:middle line:84%
Eigenspaces of T mu T mu
star have the G action.

01:04:23.730 --> 01:04:28.190 align:middle line:84%
And except for the
constant functions--

01:04:28.190 --> 01:04:31.830 align:middle line:84%
so the constant functions are an
eigenspace of T mu, T mu star.

01:04:31.830 --> 01:04:34.360 align:middle line:84%
But all the other ones,
it's a nontrivial action.

01:04:34.360 --> 01:04:42.170 align:middle line:90%


01:04:42.170 --> 01:04:44.790 align:middle line:84%
Let's suppose that for a moment
and see why it's helpful.

01:04:44.790 --> 01:04:46.970 align:middle line:84%
And then we can think
more carefully about what

01:04:46.970 --> 01:04:48.630 align:middle line:90%
exactly are the eigenspaces.

01:04:48.630 --> 01:04:59.690 align:middle line:90%


01:04:59.690 --> 01:05:00.470 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:05:00.470 --> 01:05:10.290 align:middle line:90%


01:05:10.290 --> 01:05:12.690 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:12.690 --> 01:05:23.460 align:middle line:84%
So that tells us that each
sigma i has a multiplicity which

01:05:23.460 --> 01:05:25.440 align:middle line:90%
is at least d plus 1 over 2.

01:05:25.440 --> 01:05:28.300 align:middle line:90%


01:05:28.300 --> 01:05:31.660 align:middle line:84%
And we really care about
the biggest singular vector.

01:05:31.660 --> 01:05:34.200 align:middle line:84%
There's not just one
biggest singular vector,

01:05:34.200 --> 01:05:38.700 align:middle line:84%
but there's a whole singular
subspace of a big dimension.

01:05:38.700 --> 01:05:43.460 align:middle line:84%
And all of those vectors have
this large singular value.

01:05:43.460 --> 01:05:44.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:44.780 --> 01:05:48.500 align:middle line:84%
So now another fact
from linear algebra

01:05:48.500 --> 01:05:52.020 align:middle line:84%
is that if you add up the
singular values squared

01:05:52.020 --> 01:05:58.380 align:middle line:84%
of the matrix with
multiplicity, that

01:05:58.380 --> 01:06:01.060 align:middle line:84%
is the Hilbert-Schmidt
norm of the matrix.

01:06:01.060 --> 01:06:03.230 align:middle line:84%
So it's the sum of the
entries of the matrix.

01:06:03.230 --> 01:06:12.940 align:middle line:90%


01:06:12.940 --> 01:06:15.580 align:middle line:84%
So this is a matrix where
the rows and columns

01:06:15.580 --> 01:06:17.260 align:middle line:90%
are indexed by our group, g.

01:06:17.260 --> 01:06:19.750 align:middle line:90%
So it has an entry, g1, g2.

01:06:19.750 --> 01:06:21.920 align:middle line:84%
And it's the sum of
the entries squared.

01:06:21.920 --> 01:06:30.590 align:middle line:90%


01:06:30.590 --> 01:06:32.960 align:middle line:84%
Does this look familiar to
people from linear algebra?

01:06:32.960 --> 01:06:36.430 align:middle line:90%


01:06:36.430 --> 01:06:37.430 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:37.430 --> 01:06:41.270 align:middle line:84%
Now, the entries of our
matrix, we can read off.

01:06:41.270 --> 01:06:48.570 align:middle line:84%
It's the sum g1 g2 mu of
something like g1 g2 inverse.

01:06:48.570 --> 01:06:52.470 align:middle line:84%
This might not be exactly
right, but it's the right idea.

01:06:52.470 --> 01:06:54.030 align:middle line:90%
That's the entry.

01:06:54.030 --> 01:06:57.510 align:middle line:90%
And then we're squaring it.

01:06:57.510 --> 01:07:02.030 align:middle line:84%
And so that's the size of
the group times the sum of mu

01:07:02.030 --> 01:07:02.740 align:middle line:90%
of g squared.

01:07:02.740 --> 01:07:06.110 align:middle line:90%


01:07:06.110 --> 01:07:06.610 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:07:06.610 --> 01:07:09.910 align:middle line:90%
So that's the right-hand side.

01:07:09.910 --> 01:07:13.010 align:middle line:84%
And over here, we're
counting with multiplicity.

01:07:13.010 --> 01:07:15.430 align:middle line:84%
And the multiplicity
is always large.

01:07:15.430 --> 01:07:18.760 align:middle line:84%
So this is at least
d plus 1 over 2

01:07:18.760 --> 01:07:21.870 align:middle line:90%
times sigma 1 of T mu squared.

01:07:21.870 --> 01:07:30.070 align:middle line:90%


01:07:30.070 --> 01:07:32.320 align:middle line:84%
So there's an important
difference between the sigma 1

01:07:32.320 --> 01:07:33.300 align:middle line:90%
and sigma 0.

01:07:33.300 --> 01:07:36.200 align:middle line:84%
The sigma 0 went with
the constant functions.

01:07:36.200 --> 01:07:38.600 align:middle line:84%
That lives in a
space of dimension 1.

01:07:38.600 --> 01:07:42.000 align:middle line:84%
But anybody else lives in
a big dimensional space.

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:46.760 align:middle line:84%
And so that gets
counted many times.

01:07:46.760 --> 01:07:48.740 align:middle line:84%
And that changes
the playing field.

01:07:48.740 --> 01:07:55.560 align:middle line:90%


01:07:55.560 --> 01:07:58.638 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: What is d here?

01:07:58.638 --> 01:07:59.680 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: What is d?

01:07:59.680 --> 01:08:00.890 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, d is p.

01:08:00.890 --> 01:08:01.390 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

01:08:01.390 --> 01:08:04.720 align:middle line:90%


01:08:04.720 --> 01:08:07.360 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

01:08:07.360 --> 01:08:09.500 align:middle line:90%
Is it right up there?

01:08:09.500 --> 01:08:10.000 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:12.760 align:middle line:84%
So d is the dimension
of the representation.

01:08:12.760 --> 01:08:13.820 align:middle line:90%
That's why I put it.

01:08:13.820 --> 01:08:16.359 align:middle line:90%
But it was just a mistake.

01:08:16.359 --> 01:08:17.880 align:middle line:84%
It's supposed to
be p plus 1 over 2.

01:08:17.880 --> 01:08:20.420 align:middle line:90%


01:08:20.420 --> 01:08:24.479 align:middle line:84%
So what needs to be
spelled out more carefully?

01:08:24.479 --> 01:08:26.979 align:middle line:84%
I think we should just spell
out a little more carefully why

01:08:26.979 --> 01:08:28.810 align:middle line:84%
the eigenspaces
have this G action.

01:08:28.810 --> 01:08:56.819 align:middle line:90%


01:08:56.819 --> 01:08:57.319 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:57.319 --> 01:09:00.100 align:middle line:84%
So first of all,
what is T mu star?

01:09:00.100 --> 01:09:04.939 align:middle line:84%
Let's say mu star of G
is just mu of G inverse.

01:09:04.939 --> 01:09:07.740 align:middle line:84%
And if you write down the
definition of the adjoint

01:09:07.740 --> 01:09:09.580 align:middle line:84%
and play around a
little bit, you'll

01:09:09.580 --> 01:09:14.210 align:middle line:84%
see that T mu star is
just T of mu new star.

01:09:14.210 --> 01:09:16.790 align:middle line:90%


01:09:16.790 --> 01:09:21.689 align:middle line:84%
So T mu T mu star of
f is just you take f.

01:09:21.689 --> 01:09:23.390 align:middle line:90%
You convolve it with mu star.

01:09:23.390 --> 01:09:25.910 align:middle line:84%
And then you
convolve it with mu.

01:09:25.910 --> 01:09:29.640 align:middle line:84%
So it's T of mu
convolved with mu star.

01:09:29.640 --> 01:09:34.189 align:middle line:90%


01:09:34.189 --> 01:09:35.270 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:35.270 --> 01:09:38.510 align:middle line:84%
So our operator is still
just a convolution operator,

01:09:38.510 --> 01:09:41.149 align:middle line:84%
just convolving by something
slightly different.

01:09:41.149 --> 01:09:45.470 align:middle line:84%
And now we want to see
that convolution commutes

01:09:45.470 --> 01:09:49.689 align:middle line:90%
with some symmetries of g.

01:09:49.689 --> 01:09:50.189 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:50.189 --> 01:09:54.870 align:middle line:84%
So our convolution has been
defined to be on the right.

01:09:54.870 --> 01:09:57.910 align:middle line:84%
And so I think it's supposed to
commute with the symmetries of f

01:09:57.910 --> 01:09:59.430 align:middle line:90%
on the left.

01:09:59.430 --> 01:10:06.390 align:middle line:84%
So let's say the left
action of g on f with h

01:10:06.390 --> 01:10:09.810 align:middle line:90%
is f of g inverse h.

01:10:09.810 --> 01:10:13.720 align:middle line:90%


01:10:13.720 --> 01:10:19.720 align:middle line:84%
I want to say that convolution
commutes with this action.

01:10:19.720 --> 01:10:27.720 align:middle line:84%
So I want to claim that
for any measure in nu,

01:10:27.720 --> 01:10:33.440 align:middle line:84%
If I take T nu of
left action g of f,

01:10:33.440 --> 01:10:36.620 align:middle line:90%
this is left action g T nu of f.

01:10:36.620 --> 01:10:39.100 align:middle line:90%


01:10:39.100 --> 01:10:39.600 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:10:39.600 --> 01:10:41.642 align:middle line:84%
Cross my finger that I
wrote everything correctly

01:10:41.642 --> 01:10:44.865 align:middle line:90%
so this is true.

01:10:44.865 --> 01:10:49.950 align:middle line:84%
T nu of left action
g of f at some--

01:10:49.950 --> 01:10:52.520 align:middle line:90%


01:10:52.520 --> 01:10:55.520 align:middle line:90%
let's say I evaluate that at x.

01:10:55.520 --> 01:11:00.520 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to convolve
this function with nu.

01:11:00.520 --> 01:11:03.960 align:middle line:84%
So it's Lgf convolved
with nu at x.

01:11:03.960 --> 01:11:11.980 align:middle line:84%
So it's the sum x1 x2 equals
x Lg f of x1 nu of x2.

01:11:11.980 --> 01:11:15.570 align:middle line:90%


01:11:15.570 --> 01:11:24.500 align:middle line:84%
So that's the sum x1 x2 equals
x f of g inverse x1 nu of x2.

01:11:24.500 --> 01:11:28.530 align:middle line:90%


01:11:28.530 --> 01:11:29.410 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:11:29.410 --> 01:11:34.490 align:middle line:84%
So the product of these
two guys is g inverse x.

01:11:34.490 --> 01:11:38.730 align:middle line:84%
So really, the product
x1 tilde times x2 tilde

01:11:38.730 --> 01:11:49.380 align:middle line:84%
is g inverse x f of x1
tilde nu of x2 tilde.

01:11:49.380 --> 01:11:55.010 align:middle line:90%


01:11:55.010 --> 01:12:00.930 align:middle line:84%
So that is T nu of f
evaluated at g inverse x.

01:12:00.930 --> 01:12:07.006 align:middle line:90%
So that's Lg of T nu of f of x.

01:12:07.006 --> 01:12:07.506 align:middle line:90%
Phew.

01:12:07.506 --> 01:12:12.665 align:middle line:90%


01:12:12.665 --> 01:12:15.420 align:middle line:84%
You probably can see that
I'm not a very algebraically

01:12:15.420 --> 01:12:16.560 align:middle line:90%
minded person.

01:12:16.560 --> 01:12:20.340 align:middle line:84%
I think probably a more
highbrow proof of this

01:12:20.340 --> 01:12:22.340 align:middle line:84%
says something about
acting on the left commutes

01:12:22.340 --> 01:12:25.460 align:middle line:90%
with acting on the right.

01:12:25.460 --> 01:12:28.700 align:middle line:90%
Anyway, OK.

01:12:28.700 --> 01:12:34.060 align:middle line:84%
So the group acts on functions,
and that action commutes

01:12:34.060 --> 01:12:34.960 align:middle line:90%
with this.

01:12:34.960 --> 01:12:40.420 align:middle line:84%
So if you have an eigenspace of
this, the group will act on it.

01:12:40.420 --> 01:12:42.380 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:12:42.380 --> 01:12:52.100 align:middle line:84%
So if T nu of f is lambda
f, then T nu of Lgf

01:12:52.100 --> 01:12:58.060 align:middle line:84%
will be Lg T nu of f,
which is Lg of lambda f,

01:12:58.060 --> 01:13:00.060 align:middle line:90%
which is lambda Lg of f.

01:13:00.060 --> 01:13:02.580 align:middle line:90%


01:13:02.580 --> 01:13:08.610 align:middle line:84%
So g acts on V lambda,
the eigenspace.

01:13:08.610 --> 01:13:12.470 align:middle line:90%


01:13:12.470 --> 01:13:13.150 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:13.150 --> 01:13:16.610 align:middle line:90%
So that fleshes out this.

01:13:16.610 --> 01:13:24.170 align:middle line:90%


01:13:24.170 --> 01:13:24.670 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:24.670 --> 01:13:28.630 align:middle line:90%


01:13:28.630 --> 01:13:29.430 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:13:29.430 --> 01:13:33.150 align:middle line:84%
So let's do a quick
application of this

01:13:33.150 --> 01:13:36.430 align:middle line:84%
to see what we have
learned about mixing.

01:13:36.430 --> 01:13:41.310 align:middle line:84%
So remember that we already know
that this thing is bounded by 1.

01:13:41.310 --> 01:13:42.990 align:middle line:84%
And it's not at all
clear whether this

01:13:42.990 --> 01:13:44.410 align:middle line:90%
is bigger or smaller than 1.

01:13:44.410 --> 01:13:46.550 align:middle line:90%
It depends upon mu.

01:13:46.550 --> 01:13:50.470 align:middle line:84%
If this is bigger than 1,
then this is kind of useless.

01:13:50.470 --> 01:13:52.190 align:middle line:84%
But if this is smaller
than 1, then it

01:13:52.190 --> 01:13:55.250 align:middle line:90%
gives us some new information.

01:13:55.250 --> 01:13:55.750 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:55.750 --> 01:14:05.032 align:middle line:90%


01:14:05.032 --> 01:14:06.740 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: One question
about proposition.

01:14:06.740 --> 01:14:07.840 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah?

01:14:07.840 --> 01:14:11.280 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Does it require the
existence of the representation

01:14:11.280 --> 01:14:13.220 align:middle line:90%
of degree p plus 1 over 2?

01:14:13.220 --> 01:14:15.880 align:middle line:90%


01:14:15.880 --> 01:14:18.340 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Not exactly.

01:14:18.340 --> 01:14:21.040 align:middle line:84%
This operator here
has eigenspaces.

01:14:21.040 --> 01:14:23.060 align:middle line:84%
And we know that the
group acts on them.

01:14:23.060 --> 01:14:25.440 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, there are
representations of this group.

01:14:25.440 --> 01:14:28.640 align:middle line:90%


01:14:28.640 --> 01:14:31.580 align:middle line:90%
OK, so application.

01:14:31.580 --> 01:14:36.200 align:middle line:90%


01:14:36.200 --> 01:14:39.800 align:middle line:84%
So suppose A is a
subset of SL2 Fp.

01:14:39.800 --> 01:14:42.960 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't have to be A
Selberg, just any subset.

01:14:42.960 --> 01:14:49.746 align:middle line:84%
And remember that mu of A is
the uniform measure on A. OK.

01:14:49.746 --> 01:14:53.720 align:middle line:90%
So what is mu of A L2 squared?

01:14:53.720 --> 01:14:58.200 align:middle line:84%
Well, we square the amplitude
of 1 over a squared.

01:14:58.200 --> 01:14:59.520 align:middle line:90%
And then we add it up.

01:14:59.520 --> 01:15:02.920 align:middle line:84%
And we'll get a
contribution from A points.

01:15:02.920 --> 01:15:07.770 align:middle line:84%
So we get 1 over the
cardinality of A.

01:15:07.770 --> 01:15:08.570 align:middle line:90%
Right.

01:15:08.570 --> 01:15:12.650 align:middle line:84%
So if we just plug
in our estimate,

01:15:12.650 --> 01:15:18.930 align:middle line:84%
proposition 2 tells us
that sigma 1 of TA squared

01:15:18.930 --> 01:15:27.690 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by p squared
1 over A. Whoops.

01:15:27.690 --> 01:15:28.750 align:middle line:90%
I did that wrong.

01:15:28.750 --> 01:15:30.810 align:middle line:90%
That's not good.

01:15:30.810 --> 01:15:31.950 align:middle line:90%
This is about p cubed.

01:15:31.950 --> 01:15:35.170 align:middle line:90%
This is about p.

01:15:35.170 --> 01:15:39.050 align:middle line:84%
So it's bounded by
p squared over A.

01:15:39.050 --> 01:15:44.250 align:middle line:84%
So we can see that if A
is significantly bigger

01:15:44.250 --> 01:15:51.650 align:middle line:84%
than p squared, then sigma
1 of TA is less than 1.

01:15:51.650 --> 01:15:54.690 align:middle line:90%
So if A is 10 p squared--

01:15:54.690 --> 01:15:57.810 align:middle line:84%
or, even better, p to
the 2 plus epsilon--

01:15:57.810 --> 01:16:00.690 align:middle line:84%
than sigma 1 is quite
a bit less than 1.

01:16:00.690 --> 01:16:06.540 align:middle line:84%
And so this random
walk will mix quickly.

01:16:06.540 --> 01:16:09.580 align:middle line:84%
In particular,
corollary of that is

01:16:09.580 --> 01:16:18.820 align:middle line:84%
that if H is a proper
subgroup of SL2 Fp--

01:16:18.820 --> 01:16:21.720 align:middle line:84%
so we saw earlier, if you take
a proper subgroup and you walk,

01:16:21.720 --> 01:16:24.100 align:middle line:84%
you just stay in the
subgroup, it won't mix at all.

01:16:24.100 --> 01:16:26.220 align:middle line:90%
Sigma 1 would be 1.

01:16:26.220 --> 01:16:29.870 align:middle line:84%
Then H has size which is
smaller than around p squared.

01:16:29.870 --> 01:16:33.148 align:middle line:90%


01:16:33.148 --> 01:16:34.940 align:middle line:84%
And we saw earlier that
there is a subgroup

01:16:34.940 --> 01:16:36.360 align:middle line:90%
of size about p squared.

01:16:36.360 --> 01:16:37.210 align:middle line:90%
So this is sharp.

01:16:37.210 --> 01:16:43.440 align:middle line:90%


01:16:43.440 --> 01:16:43.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:43.940 --> 01:16:47.180 align:middle line:84%
So this addresses the question
that was raised earlier.

01:16:47.180 --> 01:16:48.900 align:middle line:90%
The set A may be large.

01:16:48.900 --> 01:16:50.740 align:middle line:84%
If you just know the
size of A, can you

01:16:50.740 --> 01:16:53.900 align:middle line:90%
say whether it mixes or not?

01:16:53.900 --> 01:16:56.240 align:middle line:84%
This is essentially a sharp
answer to that question.

01:16:56.240 --> 01:16:58.660 align:middle line:84%
If A is significantly
bigger than p squared,

01:16:58.660 --> 01:17:01.790 align:middle line:90%
then the random walk does mix.

01:17:01.790 --> 01:17:03.830 align:middle line:84%
And if A is smaller
than p squared,

01:17:03.830 --> 01:17:09.830 align:middle line:84%
A could live in a subgroup, and
the random walk may not mix.

01:17:09.830 --> 01:17:12.390 align:middle line:84%
This whole phenomenon is quite
different from what would

01:17:12.390 --> 01:17:15.150 align:middle line:90%
happen in a commutative group.

01:17:15.150 --> 01:17:17.770 align:middle line:84%
In a commutative group, you
could take very large subsets,

01:17:17.770 --> 01:17:21.747 align:middle line:84%
and still, nothing
might mix, partly

01:17:21.747 --> 01:17:24.330 align:middle line:84%
because the commutative group
might have very large subgroups.

01:17:24.330 --> 01:17:27.710 align:middle line:84%
But even if it doesn't,
it wouldn't work.

01:17:27.710 --> 01:17:29.710 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:17:29.710 --> 01:17:31.550 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:17:31.550 --> 01:17:32.050 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:32.050 --> 01:17:34.350 align:middle line:84%
So that's all very interesting,
but it doesn't look

01:17:34.350 --> 01:17:36.670 align:middle line:90%
very close to this theorem yet.

01:17:36.670 --> 01:17:38.830 align:middle line:84%
Because this
theorem says that we

01:17:38.830 --> 01:17:42.630 align:middle line:84%
get mixing if our subset has
size larger than p squared.

01:17:42.630 --> 01:17:45.790 align:middle line:90%
And this is a subset of size 4.

01:17:45.790 --> 01:17:49.910 align:middle line:84%
So we will have to think some
more about how to do this.

01:17:49.910 --> 01:17:53.660 align:middle line:84%
And we will talk
about that next time.

01:17:53.660 --> 01:18:01.000 align:middle line:90%